column12: Rodenticide and method of screening
column13: A rodenticide which is non-toxic to humans, domestic animals and livestock comprises a water-retentive material as the active ingredient and a rodent attractant. Preferably the water-retentive material is cellulosic material. In certain embodiments the water-retentive material comprises alpha-cellulose. In one preferred embodiment the cellulosic material comprises purified cellulose derived from the core of the cob of the DK 446 maize hybrid or from the core of the cob of an agonist of the DK 446 hybrid. It is considered that the unique selective toxicity of such rodenticides arises from the interference with water transport through the gut wall, particularly in the caecum (where cellulose is digested in rats). The caecum is vestigial in humans, who are not therefore affected by such materials. A laboratory method of screening candidate water-retentive materials for rodenticidal activity in the field is disclosed, involving examination of the gut (for compaction and bloating) and the caecum (for impaction).

Water retentive materials, such as cellulose, for use as rodenticides with an attractant, & a method of screening such materials involving feeding to a rodent
column13: A rodenticide which is non-toxic to humans, domestic animals and livestock comprises a water-retentive material as the active ingredient and a rodent attractant. Preferably the water-retentive material is cellulosic material. In certain embodiments the water-retentive material comprises alpha-cellulose. In one preferred embodiment the cellulosic material comprises purified cellulose derived from the core of the cob of the DK 446 maize hybrid or from the core of the cob of an agonist of the DK 446 hybrid. It is considered that the unique selective toxicity of such rodenticides arises from the interference with water transport through the gut wall, particularly in the caecum (where cellulose is digested in rats), thus compromising the normal digestion process in rodents. The caecum is vestigial in humans, who are not therefore affected by such materials. A laboratory method of screening candidate water-retentive materials for rodenticidal activity in the field is disclosed involving feeding rodents with the candidate materials and either measuring weight loss in the rodents or testing the rodents to determine whether or to what extent water transport through the wall of the gut has been disrupted, eg by examination of the gut (for compaction and bloating), the caecum and/or intestine (for impaction or compaction) or thymus gland (for size or condition).

column12: COMPOSITE RODENTICIDE
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a rodenticide composed of a water-retentive rodenticidal material.

SOLUTION: The non-toxic rodenticide comprises a water-retentive material such as α-cellulose (10) encapsulated with an enteric coating (11) of a gastroresistant material such as a glassy amylase or an acrylic polymer. The enteric coating can be a pH-sensitive material, a redox-sensitive material or a material enzymatically broken down by enzymes in the gastrointestinal system so as to release the water-retentive material at a site such as the caecum, e.g. where it is particularly effective in disrupting water transport and ion transport through the gut wall. The effect causes the rat to weaken and die in a humane manner. In a variant, the water-retentive material is incorporated in a matrix of the gastroresistant material.

column12: Method of screening candidate rodenticidal materials
column13: A laboratory method of screening candidate water-retentive materials such as cellulosic materials for rodenticidal activity in the field is disclosed, in which the rodents are tested to determine whether or to what extent the water-retentive material has disrupted water transport through the wall of the gut. The method involves examination of the gut (for compaction and bloating) and the caecum (for impaction). Rodenticides which act by interference with water transport through the gut wall, particularly in the caecum (where cellulose is digested in rats) have unique selective toxicity, since the caecum is vestigial in humans, who are not therefore affected by such materials.

column13: A moulding composition comprises glass fibre and a crystallizable polymer of a mono-a -olefin, such as propylene, butene, 4-methyl-pentene, 3-methyl-pentene, mixtures thereof or mixtures with ethylene. Optional ingredients are stabilizers, processing aids, pigments, dyes and fillers, and specified are carbon black, a condensate of 3 mols. of a phenol with 1 mol. of crotonaldehyde, dilauryl dithiopropionate, calcium and zinc soaps such as calcium stearate, and natural and synthetic rubber. The glass fibre may be pretreated with an adhesion promoter such as a vinyl halo silane or an acylato chromic halide. One of the methods for forming the composition comprises passing the glass fibre in continuous form through a cross-head extruder whereby a coated fibre is obtained, the continuous coated fibre then being chopped into short lengths. The moulding compositions find application as pipes, profiles, sheets, facia boards, doors, panels, washing machine casings, laundry baskets and gear-wheels.

column12: Improvement in Means for Holding True Supporting Protecting & Feeding Drills to be applied to Drilling and Boring Machinery Hand Tools and the like
column13: 4252. Dawson, G., and Dawson, W. A. March 1. Drilling; drills.-Twist drills in ratchet braces and drilling-machines are provided with means for feeding which at the same time hold them true and support and protect them. Fig. 1 illustrates the invention applied to a ratchet brace. The drill is formed with an annular recess E', Fig. 5, which is engaged by the ends D<2> of spring-controlled levers to secure rotatably the drill in a feed-disk D ; this disk slides on guides G<2> formed on a ring G<1> splined in a ratchet-wheel F, and is screwed to fit the 'interior of a feed-nut A rotatable in the body B but secured by a flange A<2> and nut C.. The drill is driven by a die H tapped to fit it and feathered to rotate with the ratchet-wheel F, which is rotated by a pawl P in the handle as usual. The drill is inserted point first in the die, and the drill and die are passed into the brace and secured by a nut J. To release the drill, the feed-nut is turned to traverse the disk D to the top and withdraw the levers from the recess E<1>. During operation, the feed-nut is rotated by a pawl L, Fig. 2, yieldingly backed by a spring M and engaging ratchet teeth A' on the feed-nut which are rather more than twice as fine as the teeth on the wheel F, enabling the feed-nut to be rotated by the space of about two teeth before the wheel F comes into operation. The feed may be stopped, when required, by a pin N' on a turn-button which disengages the pawl L. Fig. 8 illustrates the invention applied to a drilling-machine. The die H is enclosed by a nut 15 in a removable part 12 attached to a lower arm 5 of the machine frame, and is splined to rotate with a driving-wheel 9. The guides G<2> are attached to the arm 5, and guide a disk D constructed as before. The feed-nut takes the form of a sleeve rotatable by gearing from a hand-wheel 22 and held down by a step 16 adjustable in the bore of an upper arm 2 by a set-screw 18 in a removable bridge-piece.

The bevel flange M of the drum A is driven by, a bevel pinion on a countershaft parallel to the shaft B. The drum carries blocks D, D' running on the shaft B, and is prevented from axial movement thereon by blocks C, C<1> secured to the shaft. A Fur Cutting and Blowing Machine.
column13: 3840. Booth, W. D., [Yule, G.]. Feb. 16. Separating fur.- Machine for cutting off and separating the fur from scraps of rabbit, hare, beaver, rutria, and like skins and tails for subsequent use in felting &c. The machine consists of three parts : - an automatic feeder c, which may be of usual construction, a fur-cutting device b, and a blower or separator a, which may also be of wellknown type. Beneath a hinged hopper is mounted an adjustable drum d, bearing spiral knife blades d<1>, which in conjunction with a stationary knife e serve to remove the fur from the scraps of skin. The fur and skin are conveyed by the belt f to the rollers g and picking-roller h, the latter separating the fur from the skin. The blower draws away the fur, the bits of skin falling upon the apron i for conveyance to the feeder c or otherwise.

column12: METHODS AND SYSTEMS FOR TOUCH-FREE CALL HANDLING
column13: A method, apparatus and computer-readable medium for handling incoming calls destined for a called party. The method comprises detecting arrival of an incoming call destined for the called party and attempting to reach the called party by causing a communication device associated with the called party to emit a voice message soliciting a spoken call handling command from the called party. This allows the called party not only to recognize the calling party, but also to decide whether to accept, reject or forward the incoming call without having to physically manipulate the communication device. The network-based example of implementation is compatible with many existing communication devices and has the ability to query the calling party for identification information, whereas the communication device-based example of implementation is compatible with many existing network architectures, and does not require the called party to subscribe to any particular network service.

column12: INTERJURISDICTIONAL RECORDING MECHANISM
column13: The present invention provides a system for recording an interaction including, a telephone call between a caller and a digital processing system placed over an interjurisdictional boundary, and may include a telephone call placed to at least one called recipient. For example, a caller may place a telephone call over an interjurisdictional boundary to a remote computer server. The server may use an interactive voice response (IVR) unit to obtain caller identification information, provide recording identification information to the caller, and receive authorization from the caller to record an interaction between the caller and a call recipient. The server can also obtain testamentary intent information. A telephone call may then be placed by the server to the recipient, and a two-party digital voice recording can be made on the remote server of a three-way telephone call, in which the server is one of the parties.

column12: Apparatus, method and article of manufacture for utility monitoring
column13: A utility data collection system can be implemented utilizing a serial sequence of transmissions between subsequent utility monitors. Each utility monitor can add its local utility data with the data of preceding utility monitors and transmit the combined set of data to the next utility monitor in the serial sequence. In an alternative embodiment of the invention, low power transmitters can be utilized at each utility monitor in the field to transmit to proximate utility monitors such that high power transmitters are not required to communicate directly with the utility center. Furthermore, the detection of anomalies can be tracked and immediately conveyed to the utility centers from each utility monitor. Components of the utility collection system can be implemented as code, methods and apparatus.

column12: WIRE-CONNECTOR.
Attenuator element
column13: An attenuator element, for high frequency electrical signals, at a characteristic impedance such as 50 ohms. One or more distributed resistance regions are interposed between an input and an output and are coupled to a ground pad. The impedance of the distributed resistance portion or portions is higher than the desired 50 ohms and additional input and output resistances, nondistributed, are interposed between the input pad and the ground pad and between the output pad and the ground pad to bring the effective impedance at the input and output to the desired characteristic impedance level. Utilizing the nondistributed resistances at input and output increases the power capability of the attenuator element and also results in a larger size for the distributed resistance region or regions, providing less critical tolerances for producing the distributed resistance regions.

column12: MONITOR FOR A CYCLICALLY VARYING PARAMETER
column13: A medical monitor for monitoring a cyclically varying parameter, such as the pressure in an airway of a ventilator used to assist patient breathing, comprises a transducer (1) for measuring the pressure as an electronic signal, means (18) for timing the electronic signal at two defined points in the cycle, storage means (22) for storing electronic set-up information relating to the time taken for the value of the electronic signal to depart from one of the points and arrive at the other point, means (24) for comparing current information relating to this time with the stored, set-up information, and means (28) for generating an alarm signal when the current information varies from the stored information by more than a predetermined amount. A base level of Bt and a peak level of Pt are stored as well as a standard pressure rise time of RTsu. If the rise time for the value to rise from Bt to Pt exceeds RTsu by a predetermined amount, such as the rise time RThc, this indicates a high compliance condition which causes the alarm signal to be generated. In a similar way, if the rise time is much shorter, such as RTob, this indicates an obstructed condition which likewise causes generation of the alarm signal.

column13: A method, apparatus and computer-readable medium for handling incoming calls destined for a called party. The method comprises detecting arrival of an incoming call destined for the called party and attempting to reach the called party by causing a communication device associated with the called party to emit a voice message soliciting a spoken call handling command from the called party. This allows the called party not only to recognize the calling party, but also to decide whether to accept, reject or forward the incoming call without having to physically manipulate the communication device. The network-based example of implementation is compatible with many existing communication devices and has the ability to query the calling party for identification information, whereas the communication device-based example of implementation is compatible with many existing network architectures, and does not require the called party to subscribe to any particular network service.

column12: Improvements in Data Transmitting Apparatus.
column13: 1,182,879. Telegraphy. CREED & CO. Ltd. 30 May, 1968, No. 25896/68. Heading H4P. A keyboard transmitter includes a circuit which ensures that the time base is started and stopped at the correct times in spite of poor keying. When a key is operated a character is sent to line via the transmitter under control of time base TB, Fig. 1. Trip-switch TC is operated when a key is pressed, so causing a signal to pass from TC, via gate Gl, to set bi-stable B2, which energizes magnet EM which holds the key down. There being no output g from B2, gates G3, G4 give no output and so the time base starts. Apart from passing pulses to the transmitter, the time base generates pulses P1, P4 and P14 at the beginning, middle, and end, of a character cycle. Consequently magnet EM is de-energized when P4 occurs and the time base is stopped when P14 occurs. If repeat switch RS is operated the time base is not released unt il TC is also operated in response to depression of a key. If either the key or the repeat switch is released during a cycle the time base stops at the end of the current cycle. If a key which has been released in the middle P4 of a cycle is pressed again before the end of the current cycle the time base cycles a second time before stopping, so that the character is transmitted twice.

column13: A submersible vessel (10) has a chamber (16) having an open bottom. The chamber (16) is arranged such that when the vessel (10) is submerged, air inside the chamber (16) prevents water from filling the chamber (16). The vessel has a support means, such as a seat (14), for supporting a user of the vessel. The support means is arranged such that a user is supported in a position in which at least the head of the user extends into the chamber (16) during use. The chamber has a transparent portion (18) to enable the user to view an underwater environment during use. The vessel has an air supply means for supplying air to the chamber, wherein the air supply means comprises an air compressor (22) on or above the surface of the body of water and a conduit (24) connecting the air compressor (22) to the chamber (16).

column13: The present invention provides a system for recording an interaction including, a telephone call between a caller (104) and a digital processing system placed over an interjurisdictional boundary (110), and may include a telephone call placed to at least one called recipient (134). For example, a caller may place a telephone call over an interjurisdictional boundary (110) to a remote computer server. The server may use an interactive voice response (IVR) unit (112) to obtain caller identification information, provide recording identification information to the caller, and receive authorization from the caller to record an interaction between the caller and a call recipient. The server can also obtain testamentary intent information. A telephone call may then be placed by the server to the recipient, and a two-party digital voice recording can be made on the remote server of a three-way telephone call, in which the server is one of the parties.

column12: Improvements in Apparatus for Recording the Number and Value of Coins and for Issuing Tickets Representing such Value.
column13: 7412. Dawson, J. W. March 27. Fares, registering and checking; receipts, checking and recording.-Apparatus for recording the number and value of coins placed in a cash till, fare box, &c., and for delivering a ticket representing the value of the coins placed therein, comprises a box having a coin slot 4, which is shaped to admit, one at a time only, perfect or slightly bent coins of two denominations, and is provided with weighted toothed jaws 6 for preventing the withdrawal of an inserted coin. The coin 5 when dropped into the slot passes between the stops 7, 8, pushing back the movable stop 8, and causing a pin to strike and depress the detent 14, so that it engages a notch 19 when the spring 18 restores the stop 8 to its normal position after the passage of the coin. The stop 8 being thus locked prevents either the removal of the coin or the insertion of another coin until the first coin has been ejected by the pusher 20, Fig. 8, which is operated by an external handle through gearing and the arm 24. A detent 32 and a toothed segment 31 lock the mechanism unless the external handle is moved through a full or complete stroke, and on the spring 34 subsequently returning the pusher 20 and the bar 24, a pivoted and spring-controlled catch 27 lifts the detent 14 out of the notch 19 and unlocks the stop 8. The pusher 20 drives the coin between stops 39, 35, which are separated to an extent determined by the diameter of the coin, movements of corresponding amplitude being imparted through the toothed and ratchet gearing 40, 41, 44 to the drum 45 over which the ticket tape 47 passes, and to ordinary registering-mechanism. As the ticket is fed forwards to the slot 54, it is marked or perforated by a wheel 59, which is operated by an external pointer through an arm 55 and a rod. The overshooting of the drum 45 and the improper withdrawal of tickets are prevented by a double pawl or catch and by a pivoted stop. The dials of the registering apparatus may be brought to zero by the mechanism described in Specification No. 16, A.D. 1883.

PARED DE RETENCION PLANTABLE Y BLOQUE PARA LA MISMA.
column13: Pared de retención plantable y bloque para la misma. La pared está formada de una pluralidad de filas de bloques de pared de retención plantables. Cada bloque tiene una cavidad de recepción de plantas formada en una superficie superior. La cavidad de recepción de plantas está situada entre partes de las paredes laterales que son generalmente paralelas a la cara delantera del bloque. La pared está construida de moneda que los bloques de cada fila están desplazados para dejar al descubierto una parte sustancial de la cavidad de recepción de plantas en cada bloque. La configuración de los bloques de pared individuales permite que la pared sea construida con una orientación sustancialmente vertical. Los bloques de pared pueden incluir medios de alineación y medios de conexión que permiten que los bloques sean alineados y estabilizados con respecto a los bloques de filas adyacentes de la pared de retención. (Figura 5)

Lamp shades and reflectors, and holders therefor. -An incandescent electric-lamp shade or reflector b is so held by means of a spring washer e that it is prevented from being accidentally displaced, although it can be adjusted intentionally. The annular upper end a of the shade b is bent at right-angles, and is formed with slots c for passing over the pins d on the lamp. The washer e is slit to form spring tongues f, and is slightly corrugated on its underside. When the washer is in position, the turned-up tongue pieces f engage the bottom of the bayonet-slots s and hold the washer stationary relatively to the socket piece,. while providing sufficient pressure to cause the corrugations on the underside of the washer to engage with serrations or corrugations on the ring a and prevent accidental movement. The washer may be formed plain on its underside, some of the tongues f being then turned down to engage with the ring a.

CURTAIN WALL CONSTRUCTION AND FASTENING SYSTEM
column13: Discloses a panel wall construction and fastening system for attaching curtain wall sections to a building structure. The curtain wall sections inter-fit to provide a sealed weather resistant enclosure of a building. The curtain wall panels attach to the perimeter edges of the floor sections of the building using shelf angle supports. Adjustment means interconnecting the curtain wall panels to the shelf angle supports facilitate alignment and positioning of the curtain wall sections with each other. A preferred curtain wall panel configuration provides a male female interconnection of adjacent curtain wall sections. A brick cladding system is disclosed which provides a support and attachment structure to lay a brick cladding around the curtain wall. The brick cladding system includes a support rail to support a course of bricks and brick tie channel attachable to the exterior of the building to which individual brick ties are mounted as brick laying occurs.

Lamp shades and reflectors and holders therefor.- An electric or other lamp is supported in a spring clip, which is made to grip the lamp by a holder pivoted to it, and also carrying the shade. The spring d is bent to a lozenge or pear shape so that it may easily slip over the pins c on the plug b of an electric lamp, its ends entering and being pivoted at h to the holder g<1>, g<2>, g<3>, which is formed from two plates g<1>, g<2> shaped as shown and riveted together with the fin piece g<3> formed on the shade e between them. column12: An Improved Reversing Mechanism for Rotary Washing Machines and the like.
column13: 13,656. Corteen, W. D. June 11. Controlling reversing- gearing. - Means for periodically reversing the rotation of washing- machines &c. of the kind in which energy derived from a moving part is stored in a spring which operates a reversing-member when a trigger is released, is constructed as shown in Fig. 1. Open and crossed belts pass over a set of fast and loose pulleys j, k, l, the arrangement being such that a shaft i is driven in one direction or the other as a fork-carrying link H<2> is moved to the right or left. A pinion I on the shaft i gears through an idler B with a wheel J on the machine to be driven. A worm C in mesh with a fixed rack E is adapted to slide on a feather D on a shaft A, which turns with the idler B. Springs g, g<1> are interposed between a saddle c closely enveloping the worm C and a wider saddle F, to which the link H<2> is connected by links and levers G, H, H<1>. In the configuration shown, a belt on the pulley j is driving the machine. The worm C is screwing to the right along the rack E, compressing the spring g<1>. The saddle F is held by a weighted trigger f. A bowl e' on the saddle c strikes the trigger f, releasing the saddle F. The spring g<1> expanding shifts the belts and reverses the machine. The worm C then screws to the left until it releases a trigger d, whereupon the belts are again shifted, and so on. A pin placed in a hole o in the way of the saddle F stops the machine.

Dobbies.-In a dobby for use in weaving crossbordered fabrics, the rotation of the pattern barrel is stopped when desired to allow the two rows of pegs on the exposed lag to act in succession to weave a plain twill by the disengagement of the pawl 25, Fig. 3, from its ratchet-wheel 4 by one arm of a lever 23, which is pivoted at 22 and is acted upon by a spring 24 to cause the other arm - to rest on an additional cylinder 8 with four flat sides and four sides with projections 21, which cause the pawl 25 to be operative. The shaft 5 of the cylinder 8 extends across the dobby and has secured to its other end a ratchet-wheel 6, Fig. 2, adapted to be rotated by a spring-pressed pawl 16 pivoted to an arm 15 rigidly secured to the operating-lever 3 of the dobby. An arm 7 is loose on the shaft 5 and is adjustably connected by a rod 14 to a two-armed lever controlled by a pattern chain forming part of or travelling in unison with the pattern chain of the change-box motion. This chain acts through its lever and the rod 14 to lower the arm 7. so that a finger 18 thereon is lowered to allow the pawl 16 to rotate the ratchet-wheel 6 one tooth and thus stop or start the rotation of the dobby pattern barrel through the action of the cylinder 8 and the lever 23. column12: MURO DE CONTENCION PLANTABLE Y BLOQUE PARA ELABORAR EL MISMO
column13: Un muro de contención que comprende: Un bloque de muro decontención en el cual el muro inferior se disminuye en tamaño hacia abajo mientras se extiende desde la cara frontal hacia la cara trasera. Un bloque de muro de contención, en el cual la cavidad receptora de plantas esta en comunicación de flujo mediante una apertura de drenaje. Un bloque de muro de contención en el cual la cavidad receptora de plantas esta posicionada en tal forma que una porción sustancial de la cavidad descansa sustancialmente entre las primeras superficies de cada pared lateral. Un bloque de muro de contención en el cual el largo de la cara frontal a lo largo de un borde frontal es mayor que la suma de las longitudes de las segundas superficies de cada pared lateral, y en el cual la suma de las longitudes de la cara frontal y las segundas superficies de cada pared lateral sea igual al largo de la mayor distancia entre las paredes laterales, tal como se miden a lo largo de una línea sustancialmente paralela a la cara frontal. Superficies superior e inferior, cada una con un borde frontal y un borde trasero, espaciadas y sustancialmente paralelas las unas en relación con las otras; una cara frontal que se extiende entre los bordes frontales de las superficies superior e inferior, con un par de bordes laterales; una cara trasera que se extiende entre los bordes traseros de las superficies superior e inferior, con un par de bordes laterales; un par de paredes laterales que se extienden entre las superficies superior e inferior, y una de las paredes laterales se extiende entre uno de los bordes laterales de las caras frontal y trasera, y la otra pared lateral se extiende entre el otro borde lateral de las caras frontales y traseras, cada pared lateral con primera, segunda y tercera superficies; la primera superficie se extiende desde un borde lateral de la cara frontal hacia la cara trasera hasta la segunda superficie, y la segunda superficie hacia afuera de la otra pared lateral hasta la tercera superficie, quedando la segunda superficie en general paralela a la cara frontal y perpendicular a la primera superficie, y la tercera superficie se extiende desde la segunda superficie hasta la cara trasera; y una cavidad receptora de plantas formada en la superficie superior.

column12: Improvements in Apparatus for Ascertaining the Colour and Density of Photographic Negatives and other Bodies.
column13: 16,813. Dawson, J. W. Sept. 21. Exposures, determining ; printing ; photometers a n d actinometers. - Relates to an instrument for determining the printing - value of negatives, for ascertaining the density and colour of other bodies, and capable of being used as a photometer with a standard source of light. The negative B to be examined is placed in a slot in the back of a box 1. The light passing through the negative at the aperture 4 falls on the ground glass 14, and is examined at the aperture 12. The light on the ground glass opposite the aperture 13 is adjusted as to density and colour until it corresponds exactly with the light at 12. The density is adjusted by turning the disc 7 until one of several apertures of different sizes is brought in line with the aperture 5 by which the light enters. The colour is adjusted by another disc 8, having apertures of the same size, but covered with tints of known actinic values. A lens 16 is used to converge the light on the screen 14. In one modification, the rays of light from 4 and 5 are brought close together by reflectors. In another modification, the density of the light at 13 is varied by adjusting a single aperture at different distances. The numbers read off from the edges of the two discs or other arrangements give the printing-value of the negative.

column13: Una caja de moldeo (900) para fabricar un par conjugado de bloques de muro o pared, que comprende: primera y segunda paredes extremas opuestas (902) y primera y segunda paredes laterales opuestas, formando conjuntamente las paredes extremas y las paredes laterales una cavidad de molde, estando las paredes extremas primera y segunda separadas por una distancia d1 y estando las paredes laterales primera y segunda separadas por una distancia d2 que es menor que la distancia d1; y una placa divisora (950) que tiene un primer extremo conectado a la primera pared extrema y un segundo extremo conectado a la segunda pared extrema, dividiendo la placa divisora la cavidad del molde en una primera sección de molde para formar el primer bloque y en una segunda sección de molde para formar el segundo bloque, estando la primera sección de molde configurada de tal manera que una cara delantera del primer bloque se forma adyacente a la primera pared lateral, estando la segunda sección de molde configurada de tal manera que una cara delantera del segundo bloque se forma adyacente a la segunda pared lateral, estando la placa divisora conformada en una configuración no plana de tal manera que una profundidad máxima del primer bloque, medida entre la primera pared lateral y la placa divisora a lo largo de una línea generalmente perpendicular a la primera pared lateral, es mayor que d2/2 y una profundidad máxima del segundo bloque, medida entre la segunda pared lateral y la placa divisora a lo largo de una línea generalmente perpendicular a la segunda pared lateral, es mayor que d2/2, teniendo la paca divisora una primera superficie de moldeo y una segunda superficie de moldeo, estando una cara trasera del primer bloque formada adyacente a la primera superficie de moldeo y estando una cara trasera del segundo bloque formada adyacente a la segunda superficie de moldeo, estando la placa divisora configurada de tal manera que las caras traseras del primer y segundo bloques se solapan cuando se forman en la cavidad del molde; estando la placa divisora configurada de tal manera que los bloques primero y segundo tienen dos patas que se extienden desde una parte delantera de cada bloque; y teniendo las caras delanteras cada uno de los bloques primero y segundo una longitud aproximadamente igual a d1, caracterizada porque la placa divisora está configurada de tal manera que una pata del primer bloque se intercala con las dos patas del segundo bloque, y viceversa, de manera que los bloques se encajan conjuntamente cuando los bloques primero y segundo están en la caja de molde.

column12: Improvements in or relating to Automatic Electrical Control Systems.
column13: 1,161,115. Control of motors. W. R. C. DAWSON. 23 Aug., 1966 [23 Aug., 1965], No. 36173/65. Heading H2J. [Also in Division G3] An automatic control system for a cutting or like apparatus having a tool 11 driven by an A.C. electric motor 12 and a carriage 17 driven by an electric motor 25 for causing relative movement between a workpiece 16 and the tool 11 comprises a sensor 21 for sensing the load current fed to the motor 12, a comparator for comparing the current with a predetermined value, and power control means for controlling the power supplied to the feed motor which power control means is responsive to an output from the comparator and to the magnitude and phase of the voltage supplied to the motor 12 so as to automatically control the relative movement between the tool 11 and the workpiece 16 whereby the power absorbed by the motor 12 tends towards a desired valve. As shown in Fig. 2, the system includes a transistor 43 to the base of which is applied (a) a signal representative of load current exceeding a predetermined value, this signal being derived from the sensor 21 by way of a setting resistor 38 and a reference Zener diode 44, and (b) a signal derived from a transformer 26 having its primary winding connected to the supply for the motor 12, this signal rendering transistor 43 conductive in the absence of an output from the Zener diode 44. The output from the collector of transistor 43, which output is interrupted when the load current exceeds its predetermined value, is applied over a capacitor 45 to control a thyristor 40 in circuit with the armature 35 of the feed motor 25, this circuit being connected across the output from the transformer 26 and receiving a voltage representative of the magnitude and phase of the voltage supplied to the motor 12, and the motor 25 is thus controlled in such a manner that the carriage 17 is moved relative to the tool 11 at a rate sufficient to maintain the power absorbed by the motor 12 constant. A braking diode 46 may be connected across the armature 35, and the system may include limit switches to reverse the direction of the motor 25 when the carriage reaches the end of its travel towards the tool 11. A modified arrangement, including a sensitivity control circuit is described with reference to Fig. 4 (not shown).

column13: 1,211,342. Radio reflectors. MINISTER OF TECHNOLOGY. 5 Jan., 1967 [28 Oct., 1965], No. 45765/65. Heading H4A. In a passive radio communication satellite, alternate lengths of the filaments of a net structure are metal coated to form dipoles. The metal may be aluminium or silver and the net may be either a polyamide, polyester or glass fibre. To protect the net from ultra-violet radiation it is coated, between the dipoles, with metal to a depth smaller than that at the dipoles; radio wave reflection at these lengths is negligible. The net is unfolded in space by the pressure of solar radiation in the gravitational gradient of the Earth, which causes different parts of the net to have different orbital periods.

column13: A propulsion and positioning system for a vehicle comprises a first gyroscope mounted for precession about an axis remote from the center of said gyroscope. Gyroscopes are used to cause the first gyroscope to follow a path which involves at least one precession-dominated portion and at least one translation-dominated portion, wherein in the precession-dominated portion, the mass of the first gyroscope is transferred and associated movement of the mass of the remainder of the system in a given direction occurs, and, in the translation-dominated portion, the mass of the first gyroscope moves with an associated second movement of the mass of the remainder of the system in substantially the opposite direction, wherein the movement owing to the translation-dominated portion and is larger than the movement owing to the precession-dominated portion of the motion, hence moving the system.

column12: SONIC MEANS FOR DETECTING COMPRESSOR STALL
column13: A system for providing a warning signal when certain sensed turbine engine operating conditions, specifically certain measured noise levels, indicate a compressor stall is about to occur. A sensing system includes two microphones placed at separate locations on the engine and a tachometer. A computer includes two function generating units, the first unit providing a measured sonic parameter from the microphone signals and the second unit producing a computed sonic parameter from stored empirical engine data as a function of the engine rotational speed. The two sonic parameters thus obtained are fed into a comparator, which provides a stall warning signal when the two signals are equal, indicating incipient compressor stall.

column12: Login proxy for third-party applications
column13: Users of organizations use many different third-party applications. The organizations use the services of a server to manage and interact with the third-party applications. In particular, the server provides a remote login service that interacts with auto-login components executing within the domains of the organizations. The auto-login components intercept (e.g., at networking devices of the organization) the requests to login to, or otherwise use, the third-party applications, and sends them to the remote login service. The remote login service handles transparent login of the users to the third-party applications, capturing resulting URLs and session cookies of the third-party applications and providing them to the user browsers so that the user is automatically provided with access to the applications without requiring manual login interactions.

column12: COLUMN BLOCK SYSTEM
column13: A system of blocks is configured to be compatible with each other in the construction of a columnar structure. Each block has four faces and all four faces may generally have the same dimensions. The width of the blocks may generally be about twice their height. The faces of the block also may contain a slot (118) to add an aesthetic appearance to the column. The blocks have certain constructions features that mate with specially constructed brackets in attaching a fence panel to the completed column. The blocks have interlocking elements or projections (122) that permit positive connection between courses of blocks. Projections of one block extend into the core another block. Adjacent blocks can be rotated 90 degrees relative to each other about a vertical axis of each block with each course. The blocks can be used to construct a column that is easy to install and structurally sound.

column12: Fremgangsmate for fremstilling av veggelement
column13: En fremgangsmåte for fremstilling av en murblokk og en formkasse for dette er beskrevet. Murblokkutformingen maksimaliserer anvendelsen av formkassen. Fremgangsmåten produserer murblokker som har en stor overflateareal-fasade sammenlignet med fasadestørrelsen av tidligere kjente blokker. Blokkene har ca. 1/3 mer frontoverflateareal. Dette resulterer i raskere konstruksjon av murvegger og en raskere konstruksjonssekvens. Fremgangsmåten for fremstilling av blokkene benytter effektivt formrom og materiale, som resulterer i høyere produksjonsutbytter og/eller høyere total dagsproduksjon.

column12: A PROPULSION SYSTEM
column13: A propulsion and positioning system for a vehicle comprises a gyroscope means (23) mounted for precession about an axis (AA) remote from the centre of said gyroscope means (23), means (30) connecting the mounting (22, 31, 32, 34) of the gyroscope means (23) to the vehicle, means (36, 26) for causing the gyroscope to follow a path which involves at least one precession-dominated portion and at least one translation-dominated portion, wherein in the precession-dominated portion, the mass of the gyroscope means (23) is transferred and associated movement of the mass of the remainder of the system in a given direction occurs, and, in the translation-dominated portion, the mass of the gyroscope means (23) moves with an associated second movement of the mass of the remainder of the system in substantially the opposite direction, wherein the movement owing to the translation-dominated portion and the motion is larger than the movement owing to the precession dominated portion of the motion hence moving the system.

column12: COLUMN BLOCK SYSTEM
column13: A system of blocks is configured to be compatible with each other in the construction of a columnar structure. Each block has four faces and all four faces may generally have the same dimensions. The width of the blocks may generally be about twice their height. The faces of the block also may contain a slot (118) to add an aesthetic appearance to the column. The blocks have certain constructions features that mate with specially constructed brackets in attaching a fence panel to the completed column. The blocks have interlocking elements or projections (122) that permit positive connection between courses of blocks. Projections of one block extend into the core another block. Adjacent blocks can be rotated 90 degrees relative to each other about a vertical axis of each block with each course. The blocks can be used to construct a column that is easy to install and structurally sound.

column12: Login proxy for third-party applications
column13: Users of organizations use many different third-party applications. The organizations use the services of a server to manage and interact with the third-party applications. In particular, the server provides a remote login service that interacts with auto-login components executing within the domains of the organizations. The auto-login components intercept (e.g., at networking devices of the organization) the requests to login to, or otherwise use, the third-party applications, and sends them to the remote login service. The remote login service handles transparent login of the users to the third-party applications, capturing resulting URLs and session cookies of the third-party applications and providing them to the user browsers so that the user is automatically provided with access to the applications without requiring manual login interactions.

The cylinder A is driven by racks on the reciprocating bed. In the case of one-colour printing it is driven beyond a revolution, and in the case of two-colour printing beyond two revolutions, for delivering the sheet over switches T to rollers P, Q and suitable delivery mechanism. The grippers E are on a shaft F having a twoarmed lever with bowls G, I. The bowl G is operated by a cam H to cause the grippers to take the sheet from the feed-board R. The cam H is pivoted at H<1>, and is operated as required by a rod 1 operated from a cam. The bowl I is operated to open the grippers for the delivery of the sheet by a pivoted cam J also operated by a cam &c. The cam J also operates the bowl M by which fingers K are raised to lift the sheet from the cylinder on to the switches T. Bowls O are lowered on to the cylinder to run the sheet over the switches to the rollers P, Q. The cylinder A is raised and lowered by eccentrics operated at the required times, and springs are interposed between the eccentrics and the frame. These springs are compressed when the eccentrics are operated to lower the cylinder into its position for the impression, so that they operate to lock or hold the cylinder and prevent yielding or knocking on the impression.

column13: An aqueous solution of dicyandiamide formaldehyde and a surface active salt of a sulphonic acid is heated at a pH, which at least in the final stages must exceed 7, until a condensation product is produced which is soluble on infinite dilution but is precipitatable on acidification, particularly with aluminium sulphate. Suitable sulphonates are the sodium, potassium and ammonium salts of naphthalene sulphonic acid, phenol sulphonic acid, benzene sulphonic acid, dihydroxydiphenyl propane disulphonic acid or the condensation product of naphthalene sulphonic acid and formaldehyde. In the examples: (1) 1 mol. dicyandiamide and 4 of formaldehyde buffered with borax to a pH above 7 were heated at 95 DEG C. until an insoluble resin was produced. Sodium dinaphthylmethane disulphonate was then added and heating continued at a pH above 7 until the resin dissolved; (2) sodium dihydroxydiphenylpropane disulphonate was the surface-active agent used. Products may be dried to form soluble powders. The solutions of the resins are precipitatable on acidification, e.g. with sulphuric, formic, acetic or hydrochloric acid or aluminium sulphate. Specifications 700,809, 700,810 and U.S.A. 2,567,238 are referred to.

column13: A resin stable in aqueous solution is prepared by heating 3.6-5 mols. of formaldehyde with 1 mol. of dicyandiamide and 0.3-1 mol. of boric acid until the product is soluble in water on extreme dilution. The boric acid may be added before, during or after the condensation between the other two ingredients. In the example dicyandiamide and aqueous formaldehyde were refluxed until the product had passed the insoluble stage and become soluble on extreme dilution. The product was then refluxed for 2 hours with a boric acid solution. A stable resin solution resulted which was useful for treating leather or paper or for crease-resisting fabrics. or for treating fibres of fabrics of wool, silk or acetate rayon or felt. The resin may be precipitated from the solutions by addition of a water soluble anionic sulphonate or sulphate, e.g. sodium or ammonium salts of sulphonated phenol- or naphthalene-formaldehyde condensates, sulphonated castor, neat's-foot or linseed oil, sulphite lignin, or cetyl, lauryl or stearyl sulphate, followed by acidification with aluminium sulphate. Specification 736,955 is referred to.ALSO:Water-soluble products obtained by condensing dicyandiamide with formaldehyde in presence of boric acid (see Group IV(a)), are used for treating fabrics or fibres of wool, silk or acetate rayon or felt, e.g. for making fabrics crease-resistant. In Example 5 a woven fabric is passed through a bath of aqueous sulphonated cetyl alcohol, then through an aqueous bath of the dicyandiamide-aldehyde resin and then washed and dried. Specification 736,955 [Group IV(a)] is referred to.

column13: A mobile vehicle lubrication unit for serving power transmission equipment elevated above ground level such as conveyors whereby the lubricant containing gear reducer unit is disposed in an enclosed body mounted on an upper portion of an elevated conveyor. The system includes a manifold system connectable to trailer mounted storage tanks for lubricants, pumps, filters, air supplies and supply lines, and transfer means mounted on a truck or trailer including side access to the control panel and transfer hoses enabling the user to transfer lubricants to elevated equipment such as conveyors by pulling along side of same. The device changes, filters, and replaces the oil in a reducer gearbox or other lubricant containing equipment which is not easily accessed from the ground level. Air presssure is used to evaculate used oil from the conveyor gear motor and/or reducer units and replaces the used oil with filtered or new oil through oil lines and hoses with quick disconnects which may be positioned on a manifold at ground level having oil lines in fluid communication with the gear motor/reducer unit.

column13: 666,262. Sewing-machines. WOLSEY, Ltd. Feb. 20, 1950 [Feb. 19, 1949], No. 4581/49. Class 112. Linking-machines.-A linking machine with a @ov of points 4 to receive the loops. of knitted fabric for presentation to stitching means is combined with a mounting for a transfer unit 17 having points 18 of substantially the same pitch s the points 4, to receive work from a knitting machine, and means for bringing successive points on the transfer unit into loop-transferring relation with successive points of the machine and for transferring the loops from the former points to the latter. In the arrangement shown the transfer unit 17, comprising a flat bar carrying the points 18, is clamped on a sliding carriage 11 traversed tangentially to the circle of machine points 4 by a pinion, driven from the mechanism of the machine, engaging rack teeth 12 thereon; disconnecting means in the carriage drive, or quick return drive, may be provided to enable the carriage to be moved back to its starting position after removal of the unit 17. The carriage 11 is so formed and arranged that the points 18 are inclined upwardly and their ends overlie the ends of the points 4 at the position of closest approach of the latter, the points 4 entering recesses in the underside of the points 18. A wheel 22 with helical blades, or a rotary brush or other device, is placed so as to engage the work at the position where the points 18 and 4 are in register and transfer it progressively from the former to the latter, a guard and guide 26 (Fig. 1, not shown) being provided to prevent the work from coming off the points 4 and to press it further on during the rotation of the point ring; the blades of the wheel 22 enter between successive points, the wheel being rotated by power or by the points acting on its blades, and ensure that the points 4, 18 are properly in register for the transfer of the loops from one set to the other, and the body of the wheel presses the points 18 down on to the points 4. The points 18 may carry a plurality of layers of work, which may be brought forward thereon by a fixed cam 25, and separated by another cam 24 so that only the wheel 22 acts only on the outermost layer or layers. According to the Provisional Specification, the stitching mechanism may be put out of action while work is being transferred on to the point ring so that a second layer of work may be subsequently placed thereon for the two layers 'to be secured together. Means may be provided for rotating the transfer unit through 180 degrees after part of its travel and then continuing the relative movement of the unit and the point ring in such a way that the remainder of the work is placed on the same machine points as the first part.

column13: A variable length track link (20) suitable for use in a bogie track has two link members (22, 24) and a releasable clamping means (44, 46). Each link member (22, 24) comprises a link pin (12), for coupling to a bogie track plate (4), and a transverse member (26, 28) attached, at least in use, to the link pin (12). The transverse members (26, 28) have engagement portions (34) with an engagement surfaces (36). column13: 14,260. Dawson, W. H., and Stott, J. June 27. Cylinder machines etc.; brakes; inking-apparatus. -In cylinder machines of the Wharfedale type, the sheets are fed to the cylinder when the bed is running at its slowest speed in order that the machine may be run at a higher speed. The machine is furnished with an arrangement for stopping the cylinder and with a device for controlling the supply of ink to the duct roller. The sheets are fed to the cylinder when the crank is in the position A, Fig. 1, that is, at the termination of the inward stroke. The stop-cylinder 2 makes one complete revolution and part of a second for the purpose of printing and delivering a sheet, the grippers being then in the position 6<A>. The grippers are then brought back to the position 6 to receive another sheet. This is effected by a cam 7 acting on a lever 9, which works on a pivot 10 and is connected to a bar 11, which it causes to reciprocate. To the cylinder is attached a brake disc 13, a projection 13<A> on which encounters a projection 11<A> on the bar 11. The cylinder being thus stopped, the backward movement of the bar 11 brings the grippers back to the position 6. The same arrangement may be applied to a machine having an underfeed. The stop-cylinder 2 is checked in the ordinary manner, and on the checkmotion shaft 18 is secured a lever 19 to which is attached a bar 20 having at the top a slot through which passes a pin on the end of a pivoted lever 23. A spring 24 is placed between a projection on the bar 20 and the lever 23. While the cylinder is checked, this spring is compressed and, although the bar 20 continues to reciprocate, the lever 23 remains in engagement with a projection 11<B> on the bar 11, and the lever 9 is thus held away from the cam 7. When the cylinder is liberated, the spring 24 is allowed to expand and free the lever 23 from the projection 11<B>. To control the supply of ink to the duct roller 25, Fig. 8, a knife-blade 26 is supported close to the roller by a series of wedge - shaped blocks 27 mounted on an inclined bed 28 and adjustable by a screw 29.

Cylinder machines with plane printing-surfaces.- Relates to " tumbling cylinder " machines, and is an improvement on the invention described in Specification No. 17,820, A.D. 1899. The machine is arranged so that sheets are fed to the upper part of the cylinder from two feed-boards, a sheet being printed by the cylinder in each direction of movement. The cylinder A is geared to a rack on the reciprocating type bed with which it remains in gear, and is provided with two sets of sheettaking grippers E, E', which take sheets from the feed-tables R, R<1> respectively. The cylinder is shown at one extreme of its oscillating movement, from which position the grippers E' take a sheet from the table R', and, after printing, carry it on to the delivery rollers P', Q<1>, and switch T'. The cylinder moves still further, until the grippers E reach the feed-board R, from which they take a sheet and, after printing, deliver it to the switch T and rollers P, Q. Lifting-fingers K, K' lift the sheet to the switches. The grippers are operated by cams such as are described in the Specification referred to above. Bowls O, O<1> in arms N, N' are applied to the cylinder, and are lifted as the grippers pass with the sheet.

Cylinder machines with plane printing-surfaces; delivery apparatus.-Relates to machines of the Wharfedale stop - cylinder type, and consists of an arrangement whereby the sheets may be fed at the top of the cylinder, and after printing delivered printed side up. The sheets are fed on the board R to front lays S, and are taken by the grippers E of the cylinder A. The cylinder revolves, from its position of rest, beyond a complete revolution into the position shown in Fig. 2 for the delivery of the sheet over switches T to nipping-rollers P, Q and a suitable delivery apparatus. Long fingers K lift the leading-edge of the sheet when it is released by the grippers E, and a bowl O in arms N feeds the sheet over the switches to the rollers P, Q. The grippers E are operated to take the sheet by a cam H pivoted at H<1> and operated by levers &c. and cam. The grippers E and fingers K are operated to release and deliver the sheet by a pivoted cam J operated by levers &c. and cam. After the delivery of the sheet the cylinder A is brought back to its position of rest by a catch V pivoted on an arm U rocked by a rod and crank-pin 1, 1. The catch V engages a projection Z on the brake wheel, and moves it back into engagement with a pivoted spring catch Y. The catch V is moved on its pivot to engage and release the projection Z by a pivoted piece X operated by the rod and cam 2, 2.

column13: 3888. Dawson, W. H., and Stott, J. Feb. 28. Cylinder machines; set-off, preventing.-Relates to means for operating set-off webs on the impression cylinders. The set-off web 1<c> passes over the impression surface 1<A> from one of two rolls G, I to the other. The shafts A, B of the web rolls are geared by wheels E, F, and H to friction rollers C, D adapted to engage, respectively, with cam surfaces K, J on the framing. column12: LOGIN PROXY FOR THIRD-PARTY APPLICATIONS
column13: Users of organizations use many different third-party applications. The organizations use the services of a server to manage and interact with the third-party applications. In particular, the server provides a remote login service that interacts with auto-login components executing within the domains of the organizations. The auto-login components intercept (e.g., at networking devices of the organization) the requests to login to, or otherwise use, the third-party applications, and sends them to the remote login service. The remote login service handles transparent login of the users to the third-party applications, capturing resulting URLs and session cookies of the third-party applications and providing them to the user browsers so that the user is automatically provided with access to the applications without requiring manual login interactions.

STRUCTURAL SYSTEM USING LIGHT WEIGHT METAL MEMBERS
column13: Disclosed is a structural system comprising wall panels upon which floor and ceiling panels are supported. The various panels are composed of light-gauge metal structural studs and tracks. The studs and tracks are mechanically connected using a clinching machine for joining metal studs and tracks ranging in thickness from 16 to 20 gauge. The metal is preferably galvanized steel. The panels, as well as roof trusses, can be made in a plant where the panels can be surfaced or clad with insulation and specified finishes. The structural capacity of the panels is independent of any diaphram strength contributed by the cladding. Field erection of the panels to form a building may be carried out without resort to cranes due to the light weight nature of the panels and using unskilled labour. Field connections may be made using sheet metal screws or by clinching. The on-site joining of one panel to another uses a mating of stud to track in a parallel configuration in which the stud is nested in the track along the joint between panels. This provides a tight, structural continuity between panels. The use of a clinching machine in the manufacture of the panels to provide a mechanical joint equivalent in strength to a welded joint eliminates the need for worker protection from toxic fumes generated by welding galvanized metal, requires less extensive quality control and eliminates spot painting of welds for rust protection.

column13: 13,781. Dawson, W. V., and Stott, J. July 4. Printing in several colours.-Relates to stopcylinder machines for printing in one or more colours on either or both sides of the paper, in which the sheets, after being fed by hand or otherwise to the first cylinder, are automatically carried through the machine and delivered. The cylinders are of the type described in Specification No. 18,093, A.D. 1900, [Abridgment Class Printing, Letterpress &c.], in which the bed is given a longer travel than the circumference of the cylinder, which thus makes more than a complete revolution. The edge of the sheet, when released by the grippers F, is lifted by long fingers G on to switches I or the like. The sheet is forced forward by a bowl D or the like on to carrying- mechanism J which feeds it to the second cylinder. In a similar manner, the sheet is fed to a third cylinder and so on according to the number of colours required, and is delivered in the ordinary wharfedale or other manner. For perfecting, the sheet is fed to the top of one cylinder and to the underside of the next or vice versa.

Cylinder machines with plane printing-surfaces.- Relates to stop cylinder machines in which the cylinder makes more than a revolution to each movement of the bed, as described in Specification No. 18,093, A.D. 1900, and to machines making two or more revolutions to each movement of the bed. Means are provided whereby, if the catch on the loose wheel fails to take the cylinder with it from the initial position, it is prevented from doing so at the next revolution or revolutions during the forward travel of the bed. The loose wheel 1 on the cylinder shaft A, and gearing with the reciprocating bed-rack 2, carries a pivoted pawl or catch E, which engages a fixed inclined stop G on the cylinder end. A cam C loose on the hub of the wheel 1 has stops D<1>, D<1>, adapted to engage a stop D projecting from the end of the cylinder. The catch E has a bowl H operated by the usual incline O, and has also an arm F engaging the cam C. In Fig. 1, the catch is shown in position for engaging the stop G, but, if it fails to engage the stop at the initial revolution, the high part of the cam C is moved into position to raise the arm F, and prevent the engagement of the catch at subsequent revolutions. The cam is returned to normal position when the bed makes its return movement.

column13: 5781. Partridge, G. W., and Dawson, P. March 14. Couplings; cut-outs.-The supporting-wires of an aerial conductor are carried by insulators mounted upon earthed supports, while supplementary insulators normally short-circuited are placed between the wires and main insulators. When a main insulator fails, this short-circuit is broken, thereby indicating that the main insulator has failed and bringing the supplementary insulator into action. The supporting-wires t are connected to the main insulators o, through tightening-devices t and a short-circuit a' about a supplementary insulator r. When the main insulator o fails, current passing from the conductor n through the supporting -wires t<1>, t' to earth blows the shortcircuit a', thereby introducing the supplementary insulator . The short-circuit a<1> consists of a fuse wire d, Fig. 3, surrounded by a core b of fusible insulating-material, such as a mixture of gutta-percha, and tar, which may be mixed with finely divided material, such as powdered glass, sand, french chalk, or the like. The core b is contained in a tube a of insulating-material, the ends of which are closed by plugs c carrying metal lugs g and disks f, each of which may be formed from a single piece of aluminium. Radial holes h are formed between the cap c and the ends of the tube a, to enable the plugs g to be readily placed in alinement. In the modification shown in Fig. 8 the tube a is made in two parts held together by the core b. In another form, an air space may be formed in the middle of the tube, the two parts of the latter being held together by cement. The fuse wire d is brought through the plugs c and attached to the metal terminals g. The tube a is supported by conducting-links i, and, when the insulator o fails, the leakage current passes through the fuse and melts the core b, which prevents the formation of an arc, the plugs c_are blown out, and, in the form shown in Fig. 3, the tube a falls. In modifications, the two halves of the tube are held by the links i after the fuse bas blown. Means may be added for giving an audible or other indication of the failure.

column13: A separator pad is loosely positioned between a leaf spring end and a top wall of a mounting slot in a vehicle spring hanger. The separator pad is preferably slid between the spring end and the slot top wall when the load on the leaf spring is relaxed or removed. The separator pad is positioned relative to the spring hanger while the load is relaxed to allow for limited subsequent longitudinal movement of the pad when the load is reapplied and the vehicle is in use. column13: 1,048,683. Seaming non-metallic sheet material. IMPERIAL CHEMICAL INDUSTRIES Ltd. Oct. 25, 1963 [Dec. 4, 1962], No. 45832/62. Heading B5K. [Also in Division E1] Adjacent sheets 1, 2 of rigid thermoplastic polymeric material, e.g. polyvinyl chloride, are joined by placing together areas at the edges of the sheets at least one of which areas constitutes a flange 3 or 4 formed on the edge of one of the sheets and placing over the edge of the sheets thus brought together a channelsectioned member 6 which acts to clip the sheets together. The sheets may be cemented together at the interface 5, e.g. by means of a solution of polyvinyl chloride in a suitable solvent, and the channel member 6 may itself be cemented similarly to the outer faces of the flanges 3, 4. A fillet of matching material 9 may be welded into the joint crevice and sanded down to present a flush surface. The channel member 6 is shaped so that its sides 7, 8 converge towards their free ends (Fig. 3, not shown). The distance between its sides at the free and closed ends being respectively less than and greater than the combined thickness of the sheets. Corner joints and joints between two or more sheets in the same or different planes may beformed (Figs. 4, 5, 6, hot shown). Resilient demountable joints may be made in which the sheets and clip member are separated by strips of silicone rubber and are not cemented together (Fig. 6, not shown). The method is stated to be of particular application to prefabricated walls and partitions for buildings.

column12: PROCESS FOR PRODUCING SUB-MICRON CERAMIC POWDERS OF PEROVSKITE COMPOUNDS WITH CONTROLLED STOICHIOMETRY AND PARTICLE SIZE
column13: (1) A single crystal, solid solution, chemically homogenous powder that comprises a perovskite compound having useful electrical properties and the general formula: ABO3, wherein the perovskite compound is selected from the group consisting of lead zirconate titanate, lead lanthanum zirconate titanate, lead titanate, lead zirconate, barium titanate, lead magnesium niobate, or lead zinc niobate, and having 0-50 percent total dopant or solid solution substitutions; and wherein when lead zirconate titanate is selected the perovskite has the general formula: Pb(Zr1-xTix)O3, wherein x has a value of: (1) between 0 and 0.44; (2) between 0.44 and 0.55, and a total dopant and solid solution substitution level between 13 and 50 mole percent; (3) between 0.55 and 1.00. A process for making a crystalline ceramic powder having a perovskite structure, ABO3, that includes the steps of preparing a first acidic solution containing one or more elements selected from the group consisting of hafnium, zirconium, titanium, niobium, tantalum, uranium, iron, antimony, lanthanum, bismuth, thorium, indium, nickel, manganese, neodymium, samarium, cobalt, tungsten, tin, vanadium, dysprosium, praseodymium, yttrium, promethium, europium, cerium, ytterbium, lutetium, scandium, gadolinium, terbium, holmium, erbium, thulium, chromium, potassium, and lithium; preparing a second basic solution containing a sufficient concentration of hydroxide to provide a predetermined pH when mixed with the first solution; adding the first acidic solution to the second basic solution to precipitate a substantially pure mixture of hydroxides; washing the precipitate to remove hydroxide and salt impurities that solubilize lead or other constituent elements of the powder; preparing an aqueous slurry of the washed precipitate and adding oxides or hydroxides of one or more of (2) the elements selected from the group consisting of barium, strontium, calcium, magnesium, lead, zinc, yttrium, magnesium, manganese, cobalt, zinc and nickel; hydrothermally treating the slurry at an elevated temperature and pressure for a time sufficient to form the powder; and drying the powder; wherein when lead, zirconium and titanium are selected the perovskite has the general formula: Pb(Zr1-xTix)O3, wherein x has a value of: (1) between 0 and 0.44; (2) between 0.44 and 0.55, and a total dopant and solid solution substitution level between 13 and 50 mole percent; (3) between 0.55 and 1.00; and wherein when x has a value of (1) or (3) then the total dopant and solid substitution level ranges from 0 to 50 mole percent.

METHOD OF PRINTING IMAGES AND CHARTS AND PAPER THEREFOR
column13: Discloses sheet of printable media, such as paper, of a special format for printing, preferably by computer, images (such as charts) which are too large to fit on conventional sized sheets of printed paper, and a method for printing such images. The images are printed in sections onto standard sized paper sheets segmented into a retained portion and a removable portion with a glue strip along one side of the retained portion. The sections of the image are printed on the sheet to predetermined margins extending parallel to the sheet edges. The printing may include inconspicuous marks along a registration boundary to facilitate registration of a pair of sheets. The removable portion is separated from the sheet along a segmentation line that coextends with a registration boundary and two sheets with adjacent portions of an image are overlapped until their portions of the image are in register to present a continuous image without gap or overlap. The glue strip on one is sheet activated to glue the sheets together in register. Optionally the sheets include pre-scored fold lines to facilitate folding joined sheets along predetermined fold lines so that the strip formed from the sheets can fan-folded for storage in a binder.

column12: Multiple source equalization design for gate arrays and embedded arrays
column13: In accordance with the teachings of this invention, matched performance of alternate sourced ASICs is achieved while still allowing for the smallest die size possible from each alternate source fabrication facility. In one aspect of this invention, the width of electrical interconnects are adjusted to compensate for differences in capacitances of a given interconnect path in devices fabricated by different fabrication facilities. In another aspect, transistor channel widths are adjusted to compensate for differences in capacitances of a given interconnect path in devices fabricated by different fabrication facilities. In yet another aspect of this invention, capacitance is added to the gates of transistors to decrease their speed, when manufactured by an inherently faster process.

column12: Column block system
column13: A system of blocks is configured to be compatible with each other in the construction of a columnar structure. Each block has four faces and all four faces may generally have the same dimensions. The width of the blocks may generally be about twice their height. The faces of the block also may contain a slot to add an aesthetic appearance to the column. The blocks have certain constructions features that mate with specially constructed brackets in attaching a fence panel to the completed column. The blocks have interlocking elements or projections that permit positive connection between courses of blocks. Projections of one block extend into the core another block. Adjacent blocks can be rotated 90 degrees relative to each other about a vertical axis of each block with each course. The blocks can be used to construct a column that is easy to install and structurally sound.

column12: PROCESS FOR PRODUCING HIGHLY CRYSTALLINE AND HOMOGENEOUS SUB-MICRON DOPED AND UNDOPED PIEZOELECTRIC CERAMIC POWDERS WITH CONTROLLED STOICHIOMETRY AND PARTICLE SIZE
column13: This invention provides a single crystal, solid solution, chemically homogeneous powder of a lead zirconate titanate perovskite compound. A process for making this powder is also provided which comprises: (a) preparing a first acidic solution containing zirconium and titanium ions, and optionally other ions; (b) preparing a second basic solution containing a sufficient concentration of hydroxide to provide a pre-determined pH when mixed with the first solution; (c) adding the first acidic solution to the second basic solution to precipitate a substantially pure mixture of hydroxides; (d) washing the precipitate and adding a lead compound; (e) preparing an aqueous slurry of the washed precipitate and adding lead ions, and optionally other ions; (f) hydrothermally treating the slurry at an elevated temperature and pressure for a time sufficient to form the powder; (g) drying the powder.

column12: Modifying the spectral energy content of a data bus
column13: Techniques for reducing the spectral content of a data bus are described herein. An example of a device in accordance with the present techniques includes logic to obtain a present bit of data to be transmitted over a data bus and estimate a spectral energy contribution of the present bit at a frequency of interest. The device also includes logic to determine what effect inverting the present bit will have on a net spectral energy of the data bus at the frequency of interest when the present bit is transmitted over the data bus. The device also includes logic to invert the present bit to generate an inverted bit and transmit the inverted bit over the data bus if inverting the present bit reduces the net spectral energy of the data bus at the frequency of interest.

Continuous process for production of ceramic powders with controlled morphology
column13: A continuous process for making a crystalline ceramic powder having a perovskite structure, ABO.sub.3, comprising: a. preparing a first acidic aqueous solution containing one or more elements that are insoluble precursor elements capable of forming the perovskite structure; b. preparing a second basic solution containing a sufficient concentration of hydroxide to precipitate the elements in step (a); c. mixing the first acidic solution with the second basic solution to precipitate a substantially pure mixture of hydroxides; d. washing the precipitate to remove hydroxide and salt impurities; e. forming a slurry of oxides or hydroxides of one or more of the elements that are soluble precursor elements capable of forming in the perovskite structure, and heating the slurry to a temperature sufficient to dissolve the soluble oxides or hydroxides of the soluble precursor elements; f. redispersing the washed precipitate and heating to the temperature of the soluble oxides or hydroxides of step (e); g. mixing solubilized oxides or hydroxides of step (e) with the heated slurry of step (f); h. prereacting the third aqueous slurry at temperature, pressure, concentration, and for a time necessary to obtain the desired powder morphology; and i. hydrothermally treating the pre-reacted solution in a continuous reactor at an elevated temperature and pressure for a time sufficient to form the powder.

LEAK DETECTION ASSEMBLY
column13: An assembly (12) for testing an evaporative emission control system (10) of an automotive vehicle which controls emission of volatile fuel vapors. The assembly is used to determine if a leak is present in a portion of the system which includes a vapor collection canister (14). The leak detection assembly incorporates a vacuum actuated canister vent control valve (32) which seals the evaporative system so the leak detection test can be performed. A vacuum actuated pump (28) performs a leak detection test. An engine control (26) initialize the pump by drawing air into a pump cavity and also closes the vent control valve (32). After the initialization period, the pump is activated to pressurize the evaporative emission control system. Once a control pressure is achieved, the cycle rate starts to drop off. If no leak, the pump will continue to pump at a rate that will be representative of the flow characteristics of the size of the leak. After the test has been concluded, the vent control valve (32) will unseal the system after the vacuum has been bled out through the orifice/check valve (31) that has been holding the seal during the test.

column12: INGOT MOULDS
column13: A cast iron ingot mould incorporates graphite in a matrix which has a predominantly pearlitic structure in the region surrounding the mould cavity and a predominantly ferritic structure in the outer region surrounding the pearlitic region. In one embodiment of the invention the ingot mould is initially cast with a matrix consisting 85% by volume of pearlite and graphite in 85% vermicular form. The mould is heated in a furnace to a temperature well above the A1 temperature so that the outer section of the mould is annealed to ferrite. At the same time the mould cavity is cooled e.g. by cold air so as to cool the inner region of the mould and maintain a pearlitic structure in this region.

Method of printing images and charts and paper therefor
column13: Discloses sheet of printable media, such as paper, of a special format for printing, preferably by computer, images (such as charts) which are too large to fit on conventional sized sheets of printed paper, and a method for printing such images. The images are printed in sections onto standard sized paper sheets segmented into a retained portion and a removable portion with a glue strip along one side of the retained portion. The sections of the image are printed on the sheet to predetermined margins extending parallel to the sheet edges. The printing may include inconspicuous marks along a registration boundary to facilitate registration of a pair of sheets. The removable portion is separated from the sheet along a segmentation line that coextends with a registration boundary and two sheets with adjacent portions of an image are overlapped until their portions of the image are in register to present a continuous image without gap or overlap. The glue strip on one is sheet activated to glue the sheets together in register. Optionally the sheets include pre-scored fold lines to facilitate folding joined sheets along predetermined fold lines so that the strip formed from the sheets can fan-folded for storage in a binder.
