column12: COAXIAL PIPES WITH COUPLINGS
column13: 1283919 Coaxial pipes; pipe couplings MIRRLEES BLACKSTONE Ltd 24 Oct 1969 [30 Oct 1968] 51351/68 Headings F2G and F2P [Also in Division G1] The inner and outer tubes of a coaxial pipe are spaced by a relatively rigid helix, so that fluid can flow in the inner and/or outer tubes. Couplings may be fitted to the pipe ends. A tube for conveying fluid under high pressure, e.g. to a fuel injection engine, comprises a thick-walled inner tube 10, separated by a helical metal spring 11 from outer tube 12, thus allowing the pipe to be bent and clamped without collapsing the outer tube or disturbing the coaxial relationship. The annular space may also contain an electrical resistance wire 30 or hot or cold fluid, to control the temperature of the inner tube. The pipe is coupled to, e.g., a fuel pump discharge union 16 by a connector 14, which has a threaded bore 15 adapted to receive the union 16, and a groove 18 containing an 0-ring seal 19, alternatively, groove 18 may be cut in union 16. The inner tube 10 protrudes sufficiently from outer tube 12 to seat within the bore of union 16, a seal being made by collar 21. Counterbore 22 accommodates outer tube 12 and a high pressure seal comprising ring 24, welded to pipe 12 using welding material 25, compressible packing rings 26 and externally flanged collar 27. The seal is compressed by screwing internally threaded and internally flanged sleeve 29 on to connector 14. A channel 23 may connect counter bore 22 to groove 20 which is in turn connected to a drain or reservoir as indicated schematically by arrow D, so that any fluid leaking to outer tube 12 from inner tube 11 is removed. The reservoir may be provided with a float which actuates an alarm when moved by the collection of fluid from the outer tube. Alternatively, outer tube 12 may contain a fluid under low pressure which, will be increased by any leakage from the inner tube and this increase in pressure can be used to actuate a pressure sensitive alarm system. Where the pipe is only required to transport fluids at moderate pressure the seal between the outer tube and the connector may be made by a simple 0-ring (55, Fig. 2, not shown).

column12: New water-soluble monoazo dyestuffs containing sulphonamide groups
column13: The invention comprises water-soluble monoazo dyes of formula <FORM:0913670/IV (b)/1> wherein B is the residue of a coupling component containing at least one sulphonic acid group, and R1 and R2 are hydrogen atoms or alkyl, substituted alkyl, cycloalkyl, aralkyl or aryl radicals or may be joined to form a heterocyclic ring with the nitrogen atom. column13: Cette invention concerne une poudre chimiquement homogène en solution solide, monocristaux d'un composé de perovskite de plomb zirconate titanate. Un procédé de production de cette poudre consiste à :(a) préparer une première solution acide conte nant des ions zirconium et titane, et éventuellement d'autres ions; (b) préparer une seconde solution basique contenant une concentration suffisante d'hydroxide pour obtenir un pH déterminé lorsqu'on la mélange à la première solution; (c) ajouter la première solution acide à la seconde solution basique pour précipiter un mélange sensiblement pur d'hydroxides; (d) laver le précipité et ajouter un composé de plomb; (e) préparer une boue aqueuse du précipité lavé et ajouter des ions de plomb, et éventuellement d'autres ions; (f) traiter par procédé hydrothermique la boue à une température et une pression élevées pendant un temps suffisamment long pour former la poudre; (g) sécher la poudre .

column13: A system of blocks is configured to be compatible with each other in the construction of a columnar structure. Each block has four faces and all four faces may generally have the same dimensions. The width of the blocks may generally be about twice their height. The faces of the block also may contain a slot to add an aesthetic appearance to the column. The blocks have certain constructions features that mate with specially constructed brackets in attaching a fence panel to the completed column. The blocks have interlocking elements or projections that permit positive connection between courses of blocks. Projections of one block extend into the core another block. Adjacent blocks can be rotated 90 degrees relative to each other about a vertical axis of each block with each course. The blocks can be used to construct a column that is easy to install and structurally sound.

column13: PROCESS FOR PRODUCING HIGHLY CRYSTALLINE AND HOMOGENOUS SUB-MICRON DOPED AND UNDOPED PIEZOELECTRIC CERAMIC POWDERS WITH CONTROLLED STOICHOMETRY AND PARTICLE SIZE This invention provides a single crystal, solid solution, chemically homogenous powder of a lead zirconate titanate perovskite compound having useful electrical properties and the general formula Pb(Zr1-xTix)O3, wherein x has a value between 0.44 and 0.56. The powder may also contain other secondary ingredients, such as dopants and solid solution substitutions, up to 13 mole % that alter electrical properties. The powder may have a sintering temperature of less than about 1100.degree.C and a controlled average particle size ranging from about 0.4 to about 1.2 microns. A process for making this powder is also provided which comprises: (a) preparing a first acidic solution containing zirconium and titanium ions, and optionally other ions; (b) preparing a second basic solution containing a sufficient concentration of hydroxide to provide a pre-determined pH when mixed with the first solution; (c) adding the first acidic solution to the second basic solution to precipitate a substantially pure mixture of hydroxides; (d) washing the precipitate and adding a lead compound; (e) preparing an aqueous slurry of the washed precipitate and adding lead ions, and optionally other ions; (f) hydrothermally treating the slurry at an elevated temperature and pressure for a time sufficient to form the powder; and (g) drying the powder.

column12: Column block system
column13: A system of blocks is configured to be compatible with each other in the construction of a columnar structure. Each block has four faces and all four faces may generally have the same dimensions. The width of the blocks may generally be about twice their height. The faces of the block also may contain a slot to add an aesthetic appearance to the column. The blocks have certain constructions features that mate with specially constructed brackets in attaching a fence panel to the completed column. The blocks have interlocking elements or projections that permit positive connection between courses of blocks. Projections of one block extend into the core another block. Adjacent blocks can be rotated 90 degrees relative to each other about a vertical axis of each block with each course. The blocks can be used to construct a column that is easy to install and structurally sound.

column12: MULTIPLE SOURCE EQUALIZATION DESIGN FOR GATE ARRAYS AND EMBEDDED ARRAYS
column13: In accordance with the teachings of this invention, matched performance of alternate sourced ASICs is achieved while still allowing for the smallest die size possible from each alternate source fabrication facility. In one aspect of this invention, the width of electrical interconnects (Wm1, Wm2) are adjusted to compensate for differences in capacitances of a given interconnect path in devices fabricated by different fabrication facilities. In another aspect, transistor channel widths (Wpd, Wnd) are adjusted to compensate for differences in capacitances of a given interconnect path in devices fabricated by different fabrication facilities. In yet another aspect of this invention, capacitance is added to the gates of transistors to decrease their speed, when manufactured by an inherently faster process.

column13: 11,009. Cracknell, F. W., and Bulcock, J. D. July 29. Lathes. - Unit lathes are provided with special mandrel feed and stop mechanism, and a bar bed carrying a vertical turret. The mandrel 3, Fig. 2, preferably hollow to take bar stock or receive a chuck of the draw-back collet type operated from the rear end, carries a collar grooved for feed at 14, 15 as controlled by a hand-lever, and one or more leadscrews 21 engagable by nut sections 22 carried by levers 24 cammed into and out of operation by a hand-lever 31. The levers 24 may carry nut sections at each end. A loose pulley 7 confined between collars on the spindle drives, by dogs 11, a sleeve 10 splined on the spindle and controlled by a dog-rod 45. During hand feeding, a bolt 20 between the feed-collar and the sleeve 10 prevents disengagement of the drive, and feed is limited by a rod 42, held against the pulley by a spring 43, contacting with stops carried by the turret. When the lever 31 is moved to close the feed-nut, the bolt 20 is removed, leaving the clutch free to disengage when the rod 45 contacts a stop. The turret consists of a hubbed disk rotatable on the bar bed 36. Three spacing-rollers maintain the concentricity of an outer separate ring. and the tool-holders are adjustably clamped in the space between the ring and disk. The disk has a groove to carry the stops previously referred to, and the ring has a circumferential groove to receive adjustable plates holed to engage an index bolt 63. The lathe may be fitted with a number of mandrels, a corresponding number of sets of tools being mounted in the turret, and a cam shaft may be fitted for controlling the turret.

column12: Memory cell and read circuit.
column13: The present invention relates to a memory cell, and more particularly to a single-bit, dual-port cell, and a single-sided read circuit for use with one or more such cells. The cell may, in one embodiment, be used in a static random access memory (RAM) array, and may be implemented in BICMOS technology on an integrated circuit. The cell has a flip-flop storage unit (10) comprising a CMOS circuit of cross-coupled inverters coupled to dual CMOS pass gates (12, 22) to provide isolation and data transfer. The storage unit is also coupled to a bipolar read line driver (44) in a particular configuration to accomplish rapid bit line pull-up or pull-down for high speed read operation. Several alternative embodiments are disclosed.

column12: Improvements in Water and other Liquid Cooling Apparatus.
Improvements in or connected with Pumps and Pressure Reservoirs connected therewith.
column13: 14,080. Spencer, C. J., and Dawson, J. W. June 11. Single-acting piston pumps; combined liquid and air or gas pumps.-A pump for supplying liquid and air or gas to a pressure reservoir, such as described in Specification 8740/11 for use in connexion with brakes for tramway &c. vehicles and for other purposes, is provided with a clearance space S which is normally filled with air or gas and is of such size that the plunger P<2> at the end of its stroke does not compress the air sufficiently to open the delivery valve P<1> against the minimum working pressure in the reservoir V. At the end of the stroke part of the compressed air escapes to atmosphere through the channel A in the plunger. When the pump begins to draw liquid, the pressure in the space S at the end of the stroke is sufficient to open the valve P' and force a mixture of air and liquid into the reservoir V through the pipe V<1>. The pump then continues to pump liquid only until the supply is exhausted, whereupon it again draws air into the space S. The air thus supplied to the reservoir replaces that which is withdrawn by the dissolving action of the liquid under pressure. The supply of air from the pump may be snpplemented by admitting air through the valve V<6> from a compressed-air reservoir or other source. Or a port P<3> may be provided in the wall of the pump cylinder by means of which additional air may be drawn into the pump and forced with the liquid into the reservoir. In a modification, the valve admitting additional air is actuated by a float in the reservoir V. In another form a float in the reservoir V carries a plunger working in a valved chamber at the top of the reservoir, so that, as the liquid in the reservoir falls, air is drawn in through the valve, and when the float rises, is forced through another valve into the reservoir.

column12: DIRECT CONTACT ROTARY ATTENUATOR
column13: A rotary step attenuator having a housing and a rotor rotatably mounted in the housing. An array of attenuator elements is mounted on the rotor, appearing in an end view as chords of a circle whose center is at the axis of rotation of the rotor. Each attenuator element has a first surface bearing an electrically conductive pad facing the axis of rotation of the rotor, and additionally there is a blade contact member having a first surface facing away from the axis of rotation mounted in a fixed position relative to the housing and operable to touch a selected one of the conductive pads as the rotor is rotated within the housing. column13: A process for making a crystalline ceramic powder having a perovskite structure, ABO.sub.3, that includes the steps of preparing a first acidic solution containing one or more elements selected from the group consisting of hafnium, zirconium, titanium, niobium, tantalum, uranium, iron, antimony, lanthanum, bismuth, thorium, indium, nickel, manganese, neodymium, samarium, cobalt, tungsten, tin, vanadium, dysprosium, praseodymium, yttrium, promethium, europium, cerium, ytterbium, lutetium, scandium, gadolinium, terbium, holmium, erbium, thulium, chromium, potassium, and lithium; preparing a second basic solution containing a sufficient concentration of hydroxide to provide a predetermined pH when mixed with the first solution; adding the first acidic solution to the second basic solution to precipitate a substantially pure mixture of hydroxides; washing the precipitate to remove hydroxide and salt impurities that solubilize lead or other constituent elements of the powder; preparing an aqueous slurry of the washed precipitate and adding oxides or hydroxides of one or more of the elements selected from the group consisting of barium, strontium, calcium, magnesium, lead, zinc, yttrium, magnesium, manganese, cobalt, zinc and nickel; hydrothermally treating the slurry at an elevated temperature and pressure for a time sufficient to form the powder; and drying the powder; wherein when lead, zirconium and titanium are selected the perovskite has the general formula: Pb(Zr.sub.1-x Ti.sub.x)O.sub.3, wherein x has a value of: (1) between 0 and 0.44; (2) between 0.44 and 0.55, and a total dopant and solid solution substitution level between 13 and 50 mole percent; (3) between 0.55 and 1.00; and wherein when x has a value of (1) or (3) then the total dopant and solid substitution level ranges from 0 to 50 mole percent.

column13: 1,037,174. Advancing mine roof supports. COAL INDUSTRY (PATENTS) Ltd. May 3, 1963 [March 9, 1962], No. 9200/62. Heading F1P. In a mine roof support system comprising a plurality of advanceable fluid pressure operated support frames extending along the working face of a mine and each including support props 2, at least some of the frames are each connected to a face conveyer (not shown) by a double-acting ram 17 which normally advances the conveyer towards the working face, but when extended a predetermined amount initiates the advance of its associated frame. Each frame has an associated valve box 16 connected by a branch line 28a to a pressure supply line 28 and by a conduit 32 to a return line 29. The valve box 16 comprises a two position valve 22 having ports 23-26 and a sliding piston 21, the position of which is determined by the extension of the ram 17. As shown the props 2 are supporting the roof, pressure fluid being supplied to the lower ends of each prop cylinder 2a through branch line 28a, conduit 30, port 26 and through each of four pressure operated non-return valves 34. Simultaneously pressure fluid passes from the port 26 through a further pressure operated non- return valve 35 to extend the ram 17 and thereby advance the conveyer. The ram contracting side of ram 17 and the upper ends of each prop cylinder 2a are connected through respective conduits 42, 41 and the port 24 with the return line 29. When the ram 17 is nearly completely extended a lost motion device 18, 20 associated therewith ceases to operate and the piston 21 is moved to the left, whereby, provided pressure operated non-return valves 33 are open, pressure fluid passes from the branch line 28a through port 25 to act on the pistons 34a, 35a of the pressure operated non-return valves 34, 35 and also passes to the conduits 41, 42 to pressurize the upper ends of the props 2 and contract the ram 17. The valves 34, 35 therefore open to allow fluid to pass from the ram 17 and the lower ends of the cylinders 2a through the port 23 to the return line 29. The non-return valves 33 are subjected, through conduits 39a, 40a to the pressure prevailing in the props of the two adjacent support frames whereby advance of a frame is prevented in the event of an adjacent frame being in a non-supporting condition. Contraction of the ram 17 advances the frame until the piston 21 is returned to its frame supporting position wherein conduits 39, 40 are pressurized thereby opening the valves 33 of the two adjacent frames to permit their subsequent advances. Pressure relief valves 36, 37 are provided. The valve 22 may be a rotary valve and the two valves 33 may be combined.

column12: Improvements in and relating to Means for Automatically Changing the Gauge of Wheels of Tramway, Railway, and like Vehicles.
column13: 8959. Spencer, C. J., and Dawson, J. W. April 14. Electric locomotives and motor vehicles. - The wheels A, Fig. 1, of an electric tramcar or like vehicle are mounted on a sleeve S adapted to slide on the stationary axle C, and the wheels are held in either extreme position by a block J mounted on a rotatable shaft H. The sleeve S carries a wheel W gearing with a broad pinion P on the armature spindle P' of the motor. The shafts H, Fig. 6, are connected by levers H<1> and rods H<2> to a two-armed lever H<3> mounted on a shaft K and provided with a boss K<2> carrying an arm K<4>, which is locked in position by a catch L. Two sets of rails of different gauge are connected by rails, and, when it is desired to pass from one set of rails to another, the catch L is released and the guideblocks are pulled out of contact with the wheel face by a spring K<3>. The wheels are then free to be moved laterally by the groove in the connecting-rails, and, when the car is on the second set of rails, the wheels are secured in position by resetting the guide-blocks J. In a modified form, shown in Fig. 3, divided rotating axles C, carrying the wheels A, are used, and the axles and axleboxes C' can slide laterally to adjust the gauge of the wheels. The wheels are locked in position by a rod N', which engages with one of the slots C<3> in the axle-boxes C<1>.

column13: A computing device can include a radio receiver to receive a radio signal from a radio transmitter of a second computing or communication device. The method produces wall blocks having a large surface area front face compared to the front face size of prior art blocks. The blocks have about one third more front surface area. This results in faster construction of walls and a faster construction sequence. The method of making the blocks makes efficient use of mold space and material, resulting in higher production yields and/or higher total daily production square footage.

column12: Thermocouples
column13: A thermocouple sensing element, particularly a mineral insulated thermocouple element, is mounted in a protective sheath in such a way that it is resiliently supported along its length and will not fracture upon differential expansion of the parts of the assembly. The thermocouple element preferably has a helical support around it and along a substantial part of its length. The support may comprise a helically wound wire secured around a braid which provides a cushioning effect against vibration.

column12: MULTIPLE SOURCE EQUALIZATION DESIGN FOR GATE ARRAYS AND EMBEDDED ARRAYS
column13: In accordance with the teachings of this invention, matched performance of alternate sourced ASICs is achieved while still allowing for the smallest die size possible from each alternate source fabrication facility. In one aspect of this invention, the width of electrical interconnects (Wm1, Wm2) are adjusted to compensate for differences in capacitances of a given interconnect path in devices fabricated by different fabrication facilities. In another aspect, transistor channel widths (Wpd, Wnd) are adjusted to compensate for differences in capacitances of a given interconnect path in devices fabricated by different fabrication facilities. In yet another aspect of this invention, capacitance is added to the gates of transistors to decrease their speed, when manufactured by an inherently faster process.

column12: Improvements in or relating to dicyandiamide and formaldehyde condensation products and method for making the same
column13: Water-soluble resinous condensation products are produced by heating 1 mol. of dicyandiamide with at least 3.6 mols. of aqueous formaldehyde at a pH above 7 and at a temperature not above the boiling-point until the condensation product has passed through the stage of being insoluble on extreme dilution to that of being soluble on extreme dilution. The solution may then be evaporated to dryness, e.g. by spray drying, to yield a solid water-soluble resin. The pH of the reaction mixture is adjusted by addition of borax, sodium carbonate, tertiary sodium phosphate, or dilute caustic soda. The condensation may start with a neutral or slightly acid solution but the pH must be increased above 7 before the insoluble stage is reached. The products may be mixed with wood flour or glass fibres and used for moulding, or may be used in aqueous solution for coating or impregnating materials such as paper, textile fabrics, leather, cork or wood, the resin being insolubilized on the coated material by heating and/or by addition of catalysts, e.g. ammonium chloride, ammonium sulphate, ammonium sulphocyanate, or ammonium hydrogen phosphate. The resins may also be alkylated by reaction with an alcohol, e.g. methanol, ethanol or butanol in presence of sulphuric acid, or by reaction with sodium hydroxide followed by a dialkyl sulphate. The ethers are soluble in organic solvents and the solutions are useful for coating or impregnating. A number of examples are given using varying quantities of formaldehyde and different agents for adjusting the pH of the reaction mixture.

column13: A leak detection assembly for an evaporative emission control system in an automotive vehicle including a fuel tank, a canister for collecting volatile fuel vapors from the fuel tank, a purge valve disposed between the canister and an intake manifold of an engine operative to allow flow of the fuel vapors from the canister to the intake manifold, a vacuum actuated pump in communication with the canister, and a vent control valve operative to selectively allow and prevent communication between the canister and an atmospheric vent of the vacuum actuated pump, the leak detection assembly including a three-port solenoid fluidly connected to the intake manifold and a second atmospheric vent, and a vacuum line fluidly connecting the three-port solenoid to the vent control valve, the three-port solenoid selectively communicating with the intake manifold to allow a vacuum in the vacuum line during a first operating mode to close the vent control valve and selectively communicating with the second atmospheric vent during a second operating mode to open the vent control valve.

column12: Process for manufacturing painted backlit displays having uniform backlighting intensity
column13: A method is provided for producing an illuminated graphic display composed of non-flat molded plastic backlit components which serve as interior controls for an instrument panel of an automobile. The method involves a process by which such backlit components are manufactured so as to result in minimal variability of backlighting intensity. The method particularly involves molding each backlit component from a white translucent substrate whose thickness is individually tailored such that the backlit component exhibits a suitable level of backlighting intensity when illuminated by a minimal number of light sources. For daytime viewing, a suitable and uniform level of graphics whiteness for the group of backlit components is achieved by painting each substrate with a white translucent coating, such that the backlit components have similar reflective characteristics.

column13: 19,160. Capstick, R., Dawson, W., and Whelon, A. W. Sept. 22. Contacts, mechanical; signals on engines; audible signals; miniature signals.-A track trip lever is actuated in conjunction with the ordinary semaphore to actuate a gong or,bell and a miniature signal on the engine, the engine apparatus being provided with means for allowing of travel tender foremost. The pivoted track trip lever j, Fig. 8, is weighted to lie normally in a vertical position to engage the engine contact lever, but when the ordinary semaphore is lowered to 'safety' a chain m passing around a wheel or sector l rotates the lever j into the dotted inoperative position so as to rest against a stop u. The anchor-shaped engine contact lever a, Fig. 4, is pivoted at b, and its upper end rests in sliding contact in a groove in a piece fixed on a vertically-sliding rod e, which moves in a fixed guide tube f against the action of a spring s. The upper end of the rod e raises a vertically-sliding indicator n through a lever r upon actuation, the indicator being retained in the raised position by a catch p. A gong g, Fig. 10, is also sounded through a lever h when the rod e is raised. The lever a is duplicated on the opposite side of the engine for tender-foremost running, and a short vertically-sliding rod e actuates a crank on a horizontal shaft passing across the engine to the apparatus shown in Fig. 4, and another crank on this cross shaft there engages the ordinary vertically sliding rod e.

column12: Encoding circuit, method for transmitting data over a data bus, and radio communication device

column12: Improvements in or relating to apparatus for dispensing liquids
column13: 769,196. Dispensing liquids. MILLS BROS. (SHEFFIELD), Ltd. Sept. 9, 1954 [Sept. 25, 1953], No. 26410/53. Class 116. In a beverage dispensing system comprising an electrically operated pump g and a hand operated pump d arranged to deliver through a common delivery pipe n and discharge nozzle b<1>, a normally closed valve in disposed in the delivery pipe is operable, for the delivery of the beverage, by valve operating means interconnected with means for operating a switch t for the electric motor of the electrically operated pump whereby immediate cutoff of the beverage is ensured when the electric pump is switched off. The valve operating means comprises a bell crank p rocked by a foot plate s which is depressed to open the valve and close the switch t and released to close the valve and open the switch t. The hand pump, which is used only when the electric system fails, may be operated by a lever b<2> and rod c after plate s has been depressed to open valve m. The piston of the hand pump is normally arranged so that beverage may pass through the hand pump when the electric motor is in use, but a bypass e<1> with a one way valve may be used to by-pass the hand pump if desired. A similar conduit e<2> may by-pass the electric pump. In a second construction (not shown) a single electric pump delivers via three hand pumps to three delivery pipes and nozzles, each delivery pipe having associated with it a valve m, switch t and valve operating mechanism p, s.

column12: A method of and means for the application of treatment media to elongate materials
column13: 1,132,981. Textile treating apparatus. SINGER COBBLE Ltd. 14 Feb., 1966 [13 Feb., 1965; 12 April, 1965], Nos. 6312/65 and 15355/65. Heading D1L. In a method of applying treatment media to moving elongate materials, particularly dyeing travelling yarns, the treatment media is fed intermittently and under the control influence of pneumatic means to a treatment station through which the material passes. One embodiment of apparatus for carrying out the method comprises a body part 11, having two vertically spaced, horizontally disposed through-bores 12, 13, and a vertically disposed feed conduit 14 passing through and communicating with the bores 12, 13. The upper bore 12 is provided with a valve member 17 which is reciprocated by suitable means e.g. a cam, according to a predetermined cycle. The valve member 17 is provided with a portion 17a of reduced diameter which in the open position of the valve member allows treatment media to be drawn up the conduit 14 from a reservoir 15 by virtue of a reduced pressure produced at 16. The junction of the conduit 14 with the lower bore 13 through which the material passes forms the treatment station. The treatment media may be forced up the conduit 14 by virtue of an increased pressure in the reservoir. A second embodiment is described in which the valve member is of the form described in Specification 1133196.

column12: Improvements in or relating to the rapping of electrostatic precipitators
column13: 1,012,130. Rapping of electrostatic precipitators. W. C. HOLMES & CO. Ltd. Dec. 11, 1961 [June 23, 1961; Sept. 14, 1960], Nos. 31640/60 and 22741/61. Heading B2J. A collecting plate assembly for an electrostatic precipitator comprises collector electrodes 10 in the form of plates pivoted centrally at their upper ends on pins 14, the lower ends of the electrodes 10 being located in a plurality of box movable frameworks 16 which allow a limited movement of the electrodes when the assembly is rapped by a mechanism which acts directly on some of the frameworks 16, the remainder being interconnected by one or more members forming an abutment on which the directly displaceable frameworks may bang. The electrodes 10 are suspended in edge to edge relationship in rows from a fixed framework 13. The electrodes may be of mild steel plate with pressed vertical reinforcing ribs and rolled vertical edges, a clip (not shown) being provided on one vertical edge of each electrode to engage with the adjacent electrode and hold the two in alignment. The lower edge of each electrode is formed with an extension piece 21 of mild steel plate having flats welded to each of its side edges to engage with elements 17 of H-section, which are secured to a framework 16. Each framework 16 is suspended from fixed rods 25 on stirrups 24 and a draw bar 26 of a rapper mechanism (not shown) moves the framework 16 to the left in Fig. 1 and then releases it to effect rapping of the assembly. In each of the assemblies 27 shown in Fig. 8, a swingable framework 31 with rows of electrodes 28 is moved to the left in Fig. 8 by a draw bar 32 of a rapper mechanism, and other rows of electrodes are held in displaceable frameworks 29 joined together at one end by a rigid bar 30. On release of the framework 31 its end 33 bangs against the bar 30 to give thorough rapping without shock to the frame of the assembly.

CRYSTALLIZATION METHOD
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a crystallization method, particularly the method for producing a crystalline suspension of an organic compound in a liquid medium.

SOLUTION: The invention relates to the crystallization method, particularly the method for producing the crystalline suspension. There is specifically provided, for example, the method for producing a suspension of an organic compound which has a ΔH/RT value greater than 10. The method preferably includes: a process for dispersing a melt of an organic compound in a liquid dispersion medium to form an emulsion; a process for cooling the emulsion below the melting point of the organic compound; and a process for subjecting the emulsion to ultrasonic vibration.

column12: Improvements in or relating to direct current supply circuit arrangements
column13: 991, 701. Automatic voltage control. MARCONI CO. Ltd. May 29, 1962 [June 7, 1961], No. 20541/61. Heading G3R. [Also in Divisions H2 and H3] A D.C. to D.C. converter comprises a transformer whose primary winding 2 is connected in series with a semi-conductor controlled rectifier 3 between input terminals 1, 4 and whose secondary winding is connected through a rectifying and smoothing circuit to output terminals 17,19. On firing the S.C.R. 3 current flows through the winding 2 and the S.C.R,and a capacitor 5 previously charged with point a positive to point b, discharges through the resonant circuit 3, 8, 7, 6, until the terminal b almost attains the positive potential of the terminal 1. Subsequent discharge is prevented by rectifiers 8 and 3. In consequence the potential at point c rises rapidly toward that of b. The potential at d also rises to trigger an S.C.R 10 into conducting the potential at d being clamped by a Zener diode 12. The capacitor 5 discharges through the circuit 6,10, 9, 5 which has a short time period, and the voltage drop across diode 9 shuts off the rectifier 3. Current continues in the circuit 1, 2, 5, 6,10, 4 and the potential at a rises to the potential at 1 when the rectifiers 15 and 18 cut off. The current continues in the series resonant circuit 1, 2, 5, 6,10, 4, and the point a commences an approximately sinusoidal half-wave overswing above the potential 1. This half-cycle is not allowed to be completed but is terminated by the triggering of the device 3. The waveform at a comprises a constant length negative-going portion and a positive going portion of variable length. A sample of the rectified output is fed to a comparator 23 which includes a reference potential source and provides an amplified error signal. This is fed to a unit 24 comprising a modulator, amplifier and demodulator which provides a control signal for a variable frequency oscillator 25 whose output is applied to the rectifier 3. A voltage sensitive device, e.g., a relay, 27 across the input terminals is connected to the oscillator 25 and prevents this from operating when the input voltage falls below a predetermined value. The comparator 23 (Fig. 3) comprises a potential divider 28, 29 whose junction is connected through a Zener diode 30 to the base of an amplifying transistor 32. The output of this is applied to a further transistor operating as an emitter follower, whose collector supply is obtained from a potential divider 36, 37, 38 and whose output, obtained across resistor 35 is fed to the unit 24. On switching on output to the unit 24 is obtained only as the condenser 38 slowly charges up.

column12: Improvements relating to methods for sealing joints

A pipe leading from a pump (preferably with a non-return valve) is then attached to the tapping point 4 and the sealant is injected. The tapping point is then sealed off by a plug 9. <IMAGE>

column12: Apparatus for Indicating that an Electric Current has Reached a Predetermined Amount and for the Consequent Closing of a Switch or Switches
column13: 16,142. Edmondson, J., Purdom, W. A., Dawson, J. W., and Edmondson & Purdom. July 21. Current meters ; testing.-Consists of an apparatus with a fuse and a switch which closes a circuit and gives an alarm when the current exceeds a certain intensity. Fig. 2 shows a plan of the apparatus as applied to indicate a fault in the conductors on the trolley pole of an electric tramear. The standard of the trolley pole is connected to the terminal 8, and the terminal 10 is connected to earth. The leakage current from the standard passes through the fuse 6, the switch lever 4, and the flexible conductor 11 to the earth terminal 10. When the current is sufficient to fuse the wire 6, the lever 4 is rotated by the spiral spring 12, 13, and makes contact with the springs 7, 9 attached to the terminals 8, 10, thereby re-establishing the circuit. The movement of the lever 4 closes at 17 the circuit 14, 17, 16 of a battery and electric bell, thereby giving an alarm. A mechanical bell may be used or an indicator. The switch may be made to close another circuit than the broken circuit.

column13: Patente de Invenção: "MéTODO E APARELHO PARA INFUSãODE UM EXTRATO FLUIDO USANDO UMA BOLSA DE FILTROINCLINADA CONTENDO PARTìCULAS EXTRAìVEIS DESABOR". Um método de infusão de um extrato fluído usa umabolsa filtrante (10) contendo partículas extraíveis de sabor. Umaetapa é a de suporte de uma bolsa filtrante permeável a fluido,inteiramente complacente parcialmente cheia com partículasextraíveis de sabor (14), de modo que a bolsa fique inclinada a umângulo com a horizontal variando de cerca de 30<198> a cerca de90<198>, de modo que as partículas se acumulam em umextremidade de fundo da bolsa filtrante. Uma outra etapa é odirecionamento da água de infusão para próximo de umaextremidade superior da bolsa filtrante acima das partículas. Aágua de infusão entra na bolsa filtrante, sem a necessidade parauma abertura na bolsa, e cai para se infiltrar nas partículas. Aspartículas são parcialmente fluidizadas e suspensas na água deinfusão e sobem com a água de infusão para uma parte vazia dabolsa filtrante, sem a necessidade para que os lados opostos dabolsa filtrante sejam separados para gerar um espaço interno. Umaoutra etapa inclui a infusão de um extrato fluido das partículas nabolsa filtrante e descarga do extrato fluido da bolsa filtrante. A bolsafiltrante tem uma área de saída suficiente que uma vazão dedescarga do extrato fluido é igual à vazão de entrada de água deinfusão na bolsa filtrante, quando uma coluna de fluido é produzidadentro da bolsa filtrante, que é pelo menos tão grande quanto aprofundidade vertical das partículas na bolsa filtrante.

column13: 699,136. Lamp-holders. PHILIPS ELECTRICAL INDUSTRIES, Ltd. Feb. 7, 1952, No. 3253/52. Class 38 (i). [Also in Group XI] A bulb holder in a vehicle rear light (see Group XI) comprises a cylindrical metal member 10 partially closed at one end to receive a screw-type bulb, the edge of the partial closure being formed into part of a helix. The other end of the cylindrical member is increased in diameter and formed over the edge of an insulating disc 13 having a central aperture for a conductor wire 14 soldered to a ring 16 or to an eyelet having a stem which projects through the disc 13 and through which the wire passes. The ring 16 or eyelet is held against the disc by the central contact of the bulb and can be withdrawn through the partially closed end of the holder. The holder is inserted into the open cylindrical end of a plastic light transmitting cover 1 and is held therein by a metal clip 20 which comprises almost a complete annulus and which is tightened around the cover by a bolt passed through end tags on the annulus. An embossment 21 on the clip passes through an open-ended slot 6 in the cover to make electrical contact with the holder.

column12: Improvements in or relating to Drill Grinding Machines.
column13: 123,513. Mottram, I. E., Walker, W. H., and Dawson, H. Dec. 17, 1918. Twist drills, sharpening.-Relates to machines of the type in which the drill is fed forwards to the grinding-disk in a V-shaped holder slidably mounted on a rest adapted to swivel about an axis inclined to the vertical, and in which a calliper gauge is provided to adjust the holder to the correct grinding position according to the diameter of the drill under treatment. The invention consists of a particular arrangement of the drill holder and its attachments. The bracket d carrying one of the calliper arms d<1> is provided with a fixed rod f, Fig. 2, fitting into a hole in a lug on the holder proper a. This lug carries the other calliper arm a<1>, adjustment to the gauge of the drill diameter being secured by sliding the holder bar b through the bracket d and locking it in position by means of a screw pin g. The end of the driLl rests against a push-bar l and is fed forwards by means of a screw m. As the push-bar moves forwards, it carries with it a sliding bar n, which is locked in position at the end of the traverse by means of a screw pin o. This ensures an equal traverse of the drill when it is reversed to grind the opposite face. The knife-edged stop h for the point of the drill is " backed off " to a greater extent at the base than at the top, and is slightly inclined to the vertical, thereby accommodating a greater range of drill sizes.

column12: A gas permeable electrode comprising an electrocatalyst
column13: A gas permeable electrode 21 comprises an electrocatalyst which is permeable to a reactant or reactant product. The said electrocatalyst comprises particulate boron-doped diamond. The electrode may be provided with a gas diffusion means, permeable to the gas but not to an electrolyte. The boron-doped diamond may be mixed with a hydrophobic material such that it is permeable to a gas but impermeable to an electrolyte. The electrode may be doped with between 10<19> or 10<21> boron atoms per cubic centimeter of solid. The boron-doped diamond particles may be between 0.1 and 50 microns in diameter. Also disclosed is a method of making an electrode comprising an electrocatalyst, and a method of making the electrocatalyst via a chemical vapor deposition technique (CVD).

column12: Display controller permitting connection of multiple displays with a single video cable
column13: A display controller that permits more than one display to be operated by a single cable and a single display adapter. The display controller provides custom EDID information to a computer to which it is attached. The custom EDID information may include information about the single virtual display surface provided by all displays, and may include information about each of the individual monitors or displays, including the location of the individual displays in the single composite display surface. The single composite display surface may be utilized by computers that are not capable of recognizing the EDID for the multiple display system. If the computer does recognize the EDID for the multiple display system, the operating system of the computer and/or applications running on the computer may understand and utilize the heterogeneous nature of the display surface and may optimize display quality and presentation for a user.

column13: PURPOSE: A display controller to connect multiple displays with a single video cable is provided to offer the display controller enabling the single cable and a single displays adaptor operate more than one display by dividing information of a single frame offered from the display adaptor into multiple display information. CONSTITUTION: A computer system includes a computer(200), the display adaptor(216) related to the computer, and the display controller(206) connected to a monitor/display adaptor and configured to divide the frame received from the display adaptor among the multiple displays(2021-202N). The video display adaptor includes a single video cable plug and the display controller is connected to the display adaptor through the single video plug.

column12: METHOD, SYSTEM AND APPARATUS FOR PROVIDING CALLING NAME IDENTIFICATION
column13: Embodiments of the present invention are directed to a method, system and apparatus for providing customized calling identification. A method for providing customized calling identification comprises receiving a request for initiating an out-going call from a communication client, the communication client being registered in association with a network address and being associated with a communication client identifier. The method further comprises, based on the communication client identifier, determining an auxiliary identifier associated with the communication client. The method further comprises augmenting the request for initiating an outgoing call with the auxiliary identifier to generate an augmented request.

column12: METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR MANAGING INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL CALLS FOR A GROUP OF COMMUNICATION CLIENTS SHARING A COMMON CUSTOMER IDENTIFIER
column13: A method and network element for implementing a virtual PBX feature for a customer associated with a plurality of endpoints. The method comprises receiving information regarding a call. Based on the information regarding the call, it is determined if the call is an external inbound call or an internal call that identifies a particular one of the endpoints. Responsive to determining that the call is an external inbound call, the call is caused to be routed to the plurality of endpoints associated with the customer, while responsive to determining that the call is an internal call that identifies a particular one of the endpoints, the call is caused to be routed to the particular one of the endpoints. This allows members of a small business or household to share a common external subscriber line, while also allowing the members to reach one another with ease.

column12: METHOD, SYSTEM AND APPARATUS FOR CAUSING A COMMUNICATION DEVICE TO JOIN A COMMUNICATION SESSION
column13: According to embodiments of the present invention, there are provided a method, system and apparatus for joining a communication session. A method comprises receiving from a first communication device an indication of a desire of the first communication device to establish a communication session; the first communication device having been associated with a device group comprising the first communication device and at least one second communication device. The method further comprises determining if there exists an active communication session with the at least one second communication device. The method further comprises, responsive to existence of the active communication session, causing the first communication device to join the active communication session.

Based on the information regarding the call, it is determined if the call is an external inbound call or an internal call that identifies a particular one of the endpoints. Responsive to determining that the call is an external inbound call, the call is caused to be routed to the plurality of endpoints associated with the customer, while responsive to determining that the call is an internal call that identifies a particular one of the endpoints, the call is caused to be routed to the particular one of the endpoints. This allows members of a small business or household to share a common external subscriber line, while also allowing the members to reach one another with ease.

column12: Display controller permitting connection of multiple displays with a single video cable
column13: A display controller that permits more than one display to be operated by a single cable and a single display adapter. The display controller provides custom EDID information to a computer to which it is attached. The custom EDID information may include information about the single virtual display surface provided by all displays, and may include information about each of the individual monitors or displays, including the location of the individual displays in the single composite display surface. The single composite display surface may be utilized by computers that are not capable of recognizing the EDID for the multiple display system. If the computer does recognize the EDID for the multiple display system, the operating system of the computer and/or applications running on the computer may understand and utilize the heterogeneous nature of the display surface and may optimize display quality and presentation for a user.

column12: System and method for tracking the security enforcement in a grid system
column13: The "grid security monitor" tracks the security status of resources in a grid computer system. When a client submits a job to the grid scheduler, the grid security monitor creates a security contract. The security contract comprises all the security credentials needed to access the resource executing the job, as well as privacy and security requirements. The grid security monitor compares the security status of the resource to the requirements of the security contract. If the security status of the resource changes or violates the security contract, then the grid security monitor notifies the client. The grid security monitor has a user interface that allows the client to perform a manual security validation by asking the grid management system to verify the security status of the resource.

column12: Method and apparatus for brewing a fluid extract using an inclined filter pouch containing flavor extractable particles
column13: A method of brewing a fluid extract using a filter pouch containing flavor extractable particles. One step is supporting a fully compliant, fluid-permeable filter pouch partially filled with flavor extractable particles such that the pouch is inclined at an angle to horizontal ranging from about 30.degree. to about 90.degree. so that the particles accumulate at a bottom end of the filter pouch. Another step is directing brew water to near an upper end of the filter pouch above the particles. The brew water enters the filter pouch without the need for an opening in the pouch, and drops to infiltrate the particles. The particles are partially fluidized by and suspended in the brew water and they rise with the brew water into an empty portion of the filter pouch without a need for opposing sides of the filter pouch to separate to generate internal space. A further step includes brewing a fluid extract from the particles in the filter pouch and discharging the fluid extract from the filter pouch. The filter pouch has sufficient exit area that a fluid extract discharge rate matches a rate of brew water entry into the filter pouch when a fluid head is produced inside the filter pouch which is at least as great as a vertical depth of particles in the filter pouch.

column12: Seal cleansing routine
column13: A method is provided for cleansing a seal of a device used for sealing an evaporative emission control system of an automotive vehicle. The method starts by determining if a request to close the device has been made. If the request to close the device has been made, the method cycles the device a plurality of times to press and lift the seal off of a seat repeatedly. The method also determines if the seal is closed after the cycling step. If the seal is not closed after the cycling step, the method closes the seal. Preferably, the cycling step includes cycling the device at a pre-selected duty cycle, frequency and cycle count. The duty cycle, frequency, and cycle count correspond to calibration tables prepared for the particular device employed to insure that the seal strikes its seat about three times before sealing.

column12: Convertible automobile carrier
column13: A semitrailer is described which is capable of conversion between a general freight carrying mode, and an automobile carrying mode. The floor of the semitrailer, which forms a lower tier, is fabricated in a discontinuous shape comprising from the rear end to the front end of the semitrailer an angled section, a drop section, and a horizontal section, the angled section extending downward at an angle whose vertex is located at the rear end of the semitrailer. An upper tier is formed by track supporting members mounted on each sidewall of the trailer which can be pivoted downward from a storage position adjacent to the sidewall, to a horizontal position where the components of the members are connected to form a continuous supporting structure. In the automobile carrying mode the track supporting members are deployed in their horizontal position, thereby permitting automobiles to be placed thereon in an upper storage tier. An inclined plane adjacent to the drop section permits an automobile to be subsequently placed on the lower tier, next to the front end of the semitrailer, with additional automobiles thereafter placed behind. In the general freight carrying mode, the track support members are pivoted to their storage position, thereby allowing the entire space within the semitrailer to be used for general freight.

column12: Purge monitor/switch rationality diagnostics
column13: A method is provided for determining the rationality of a device for monitoring the pressure within an evaporative emission control system of an automotive vehicle. The method includes opening a valve of the evaporative emission control system and determining if a vacuum switch of the evaporative emission control system opened. If the vacuum switch opened, a code is set indicating that the vacuum switch passed an opening test. If the vacuum switch did not open, the method determines if a fail timer is greater than a first fail threshold value. The first fail threshold value corresponds to an amount of time within which a properly functioning vacuum switch should open after said valve is opened. If the fail timer is greater than the fail threshold value, the method sets a code indicating that the vacuum switch failed the opening test. If the fail timer is less than or equal to the first fail threshold value, the method increments the fail timer. If the vacuum switch passed the opening test, the method closes the valve of the evaporative emission control system and applies a vacuum thereto. The method then determines if the vacuum switch closed due to the vacuum. If the vacuum switch closed, the method sets a code indicating that the vacuum switch passed a closing test. If the vacuum switch did not close, the method determines if the fail timer is greater than a second fail threshold value. The second fail threshold value corresponds to an amount of time within which a properly functioning vacuum switch should close after the vacuum is applied. If the fail timer is greater than the second fail threshold value, the method sets a code indicating that the vacuum switch failed the closing test. If the fail timer is less than or equal to the second fail threshold value, the method increments the fail timer.

column13: Section plates in a generator frame are spaced longitudinally or axially one from the other and have ventilation openings for flowing a cooling gas. The ventilation openings comprise in each section plate a plurality of alternating right-side-up and upside-down triangles extending across the bottom of the section plate. The bases of the triangular openings are formed by the housing or wrapper plate enabling free flow unbounded by additional ligaments through the openings in the section plate, reducing the pressure drop and windage losses, while increasing machine efficiency.

column12: Apparatus for brewing a fluid extract using an inclined filter pouch containing flavor extractable particles
column13: A method of brewing a fluid extract using a filter pouch containing flavor extractable particles. One step is supporting a fully compliant, fluid-permeable filter pouch partially filled with flavor extractable particles such that the pouch is inclined at an angle to horizontal ranging from about 30 to about 90 so that the particles accumulate at a bottom end of the filter pouch. Another step is directing brew water to near an upper end of the filter pouch above the particles. The brew water enters the filter pouch without the need for an opening in the pouch, and drops to infiltrate the particles. The particles are partially fluidized by and suspended in the brew water and they rise with the brew water into an empty portion of the filter pouch without a need for opposing sides of the filter pouch to separate to generate internal space. A further step includes brewing a fluid extract from the particles in the filter pouch and discharging the fluid extract from the filter pouch. The filter pouch has sufficient exit area that a fluid extract discharge rate matches a rate of brew water entry into the filter pouch when a fluid head is produced inside the filter pouch which is at least as great as a vertical depth of particles in the filter pouch.

column12: Display controller permitting connection of multiple displays with a single video cable
column13: (0070) A display controller that permits more than one display to be operated by a single cable and a single display adapter. The display controller provides custom EDID information to a computer to which it is attached. The custom EDID information may include information about the single virtual display surface provided by all displays, and may include information about each of the individual monitors or displays, including the location of the individual displays in the single composite display surface. The single composite display surface may be utilized by computers that are not capable of recognizing the EDID for the multiple display system. If the computer does recognize the EDID for the multiple display system, the operating system of the computer and/or applications running on the computer may understand and utilize the heterogeneous nature of the display surface and may optimize display quality and presentation for a user.

column12: Method and system for managing internal and external calls for a group of communication clients sharing a common customer identifier
column13: A method and network element for implementing a virtual PBX feature for a customer associated with a plurality of endpoints. The method comprises receiving information regarding a call. Based on the information regarding the call, it is determined if the call is an external inbound call or an internal call that identifies a particular one of the endpoints. Responsive to determining that the call is an external inbound call, the call is caused to be routed to the plurality of endpoints associated with the customer, while responsive to determining that the call is an internal call that identifies a particular one of the endpoints, the call is caused to be routed to the particular one of the endpoints. This allows members of a small business or household to share a common external subscriber line, while also allowing the members to reach one another with ease.

column12: A method of regenerating an emission control device
column13: A method of regenerating an emission control device 222 operatively connected to an engine 210 of a vehicle 20 having a wheel brake 216 and a transmission 218 comprises receiving a generation request from a driver input device 224, increasing engine braking torque, increasing engine output torque to compensate for the increased braking torque so as to cause the temperature of the exhaust gas from the engine 210 to rise and regenerating the emission control device 222 when the temperature has risen to a required temperature. The engine braking torque can be increased by activating the wheel brake 216, by adjusting operation of the transmission 218 or by a combination of these. The operation of the transmission may be adjusted by activating at least one hydraulic clutch of the transmission to engage at least one gear.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR BREWING A FLUID EXTRACT USING AN INCLINED FILTER POUCH CONTAINING FLAVOR EXTRACTABLE PARTICLES
column13: A method of brewing a fluid extract using a filter pouch (10) containing flavor extractable particles. One step is supporting a fully compliant, fluid-permeable filter pouch partially filled with flavor extractable particles (14) such that the pouch is inclined at an angle to horizontal ranging from about 30 ° to about 90 ° so that the particles accumulate at a bottom end of the filter pouch. Another step is directing brew water to near an upper end of the filter pouch above the particles. The brew water enters the filter pouch without the need for an opening in the pouch, and drops to infiltrate the particles. The particles are partially fluidized by and suspended in the brew water and they rise with the brew water into an empty portion of the filter pouch without a need for opposing sides of the filter pouch to separate to generate internal space. A further step includes brewing a fluid extract from the particles in the filter pouch and discharging the fluid extract from the filter pouch. The filter pouch has sufficient exit area that a fluid extract discharge rate matches a rate of brew water entry into the filter pouch when a fluid head is produced inside the filter pouch which is at least as great as a vertical depth of particles in the filter pouch.

column12: Controlled degradation of polysaccharides
column13: A method is shown for fracturing a subterranean formation in which a hydratable polymer, crosslinking agent and breaker are combined in an aqueous carrier to form a gelled fracturing fluid. The breaker is comprised of a substantially insoluble oxidant which is granulated and formed into a pellet or prill with a suitable binder. The pellet so formed can also contain a chelating agent and an activator in order to enhance the rate of breaking. The substantially insoluble oxidant is selected from the group consisting of alkaline earth and zinc salts of peroxide, perphosphate, perborate, and percarbonate.

column12: Multiple source equalization design utilizing metal interconnects for gate arrays and embedded arrays
column13: In accordance with the teachings of this invention, matched performance of alternate sourced ASICs is achieved while still allowing for the smallest die size possible from each alternate source fabrication facility. In one aspect of this invention, the width of electrical interconnects are adjusted to compensate for differences in capacitances of a given interconnect path in devices fabricated by different fabrication facilities. In another aspect, transistor channel widths are adjusted to compensate for differences in capacitances of a given interconnect path in devices fabricated by different fabrication facilities. In yet another aspect of this invention, capacitance is added to the gates of transistors to decrease their speed, when manufactured by an inherently faster process.

column12: Evaporative system leak detection feature after a refueling event
column13: A method is provided for testing an evaporative emission control system for a missing or loose fuel cap comprising detecting a refueling event and running a leak detection test of the evaporative emission control system to determine if a large leak is present. If a large leak is detected, the methodology sets a fault code and activates a driver warning lamp indicating a potential cap sealing problem. The leak detection test is repeatedly re-executed after the large leak is detected to determine when the large leak condition ceases. When the large leak condition ceases, the previously set fault code is removed and the driver warning lamp is deactivated. If the large leak does not cease and is detected again after the next refueling event when an opportunity for resealing the cap existed, a new fault code is set indicating that the potential cap sealing problem is a persistent problem so that the integrity of the evaporative system may need to be tested. After setting the new fault code, fuel cap specific leak detection testing is suspended until the condition is serviced and the fault code is cleared or a normal leak detection test determines that there is no longer a problem. If no large leak is detected, the fuel cap is assumed to be properly sealed.

column12: Resistor grid insulator mountings
column13: An improved frame supported resistor grid used for dynamic braking of electric motors is provided. The resistor grid has a metal frame and fan-folded strips of resistance material arranged in columns within the frame. The strips of resistance material are supported by studs affixed to the folds of the strips and the studs are, in turn, supported in ceramic bushing insulators. An intermediate member is affixed to the frame and receives the individual ceramic bushing insulators.

column12: Evaporative emission control for very small leak detection
column13: A method is provided for detecting a very small leak in an evaporative emission control system of an automotive vehicle. The method includes sealing the evaporative emission control system at a key-off event and monitoring a vacuum switch coupled to the evaporative emission control system for a closing event due to a natural vacuum created in the evaporative emission control system as it cools. If the closing event is not detected, the method determines if a leak detection timer has exceeded a predetermined threshold value. If the timer has exceeded the predetermined threshold value, the method sets a fault code indicating that the very small leak has been detected. Preferably, the leak detection timer includes a first time value corresponding to an amount of time the automotive vehicle has been operating since a previous small leak detection test was conducted and a second time value corresponding to an amount of time the automotive vehicle has been inoperative since a previous small leak detection test was conducted. The first time value includes a series of individual trip times of the automotive vehicle while the second time value includes a series of individual inoperative session times of the automotive vehicle.

In one aspect of this invention, the width of electrical interconnects (Wm1, Wm2) are adjusted to compensate for differences in capacitances of a given interconnect path in devices fabricated by different fabrication facilities. In another aspect, transistor channel widths (Wpd, Wnd) are adjusted to compensate for differences in capacitances of a given interconnect path in devices fabricated by different fabrication facilities. column12: Method and apparatus for brewing a fluid extract using an inclined filter pouch containing flavor extractable particles
column13: A method of brewing a fluid extract using a filter pouch containing flavor extractable particles. One step is supporting a fully compliant, fluid-permeable filter pouch partially filled with flavor extractable particles such that the pouch is inclined at an angle to horizontal ranging from about 30 to about 90 so that the particles accumulate at a bottom end of the filter pouch. Another step is directing brew water to near an upper end of the filter pouch above the particles. The brew water enters the filter pouch without the need for an opening in the pouch, and drops to infiltrate the particles. The particles are partially fluidized by and suspended in the brew water and they rise with the brew water into an empty portion of the filter pouch without a need for opposing sides of the filter pouch to separate to generate internal space. A further step includes brewing a fluid extract from the particles in the filter pouch and discharging the fluid extract from the filter pouch. The filter pouch has sufficient exit area that a fluid extract discharge rate matches a rate of brew water entry into the filter pouch when a fluid head is produced inside the filter pouch which is at least as great as a vertical depth of particles in the filter pouch.

column12: System and method for the creation and use of surrogate information system objects
column13: The present invention defines a consistent method and system for enabling components in an information system to invoke operations that may be distributed across multiple computing platforms, through the provision and use of executable operations whose behaviors are determined from information stored and extracted from a Catalog (164) using an Operation Definition Manager (82). The stored information is used by a Surrogate Object Definition Module (96) to define a Surrogate Object Type structure which enables execution of any of the operations described within it. A Surrogate Object Manager (94), along with an Operation Connection Manager (104, 118, 130 or 132), is provided which assists the user in developing applications by providing access to the definition of the input and output arguments of the operations included in the Surrogate Object Type structure (244). The present invention further includes an Operation Connection Manager (104, 118, 130 or 132) which, together with the Surrogate Object Manager (94), provides a consistent means for an Operation Requestor (92) to invoke an operation and exchange input and output arguments, independent of the intervening network communication protocol or the hardware platform type, operating system and database management system upon which the operation has been implemented.

column12: FLEXIBLE IDENTITY AND ACCESS MANAGEMENT PIPELINE
column13: A system and a method are disclosed for context-based policies for digital identity verification. A context-based identification system provides flexible identification procedures for various enterprises that adapted to the enterprises' services, the enterprises' customers, and these customers' needs. For example, the context-based identification system determines a first and second policy associated with a first enterprise and a third policy associated with a second enterprise. These policies include context parameters and verification parameters. The context-based identification system determines context parameters of a request, or "request context parameters," when a user requests to interact with the first enterprise and determines a policy with context parameters that substantially match these request context parameters. column13: An assembly for testing an evaporative emission control system of an automotive vehicle which controls emission of volatile fuel vapors. The assembly is used to determine if a leak is present in a portion of the system which includes a vapor collection canister. The leak detection assembly incorporates a vacuum actuated canister vent control valve which seals the evaporative system so the leak detection test can be performed. A vacuum actuated pump which performs a leak detection test. An engine control unit initializes the pump by drawing air into a pump cavity and also closes the vent control valve. After the initialization period, the pump is activated to pressurize the evaporative emission control system. Once a control pressure is achieved, the cycle rate starts to drop off. If no leak exists in the system, the pump will eventually stop pumping. If there is a leak, the pump will continue to pump at a rate that will be representative of the flow characteristics of the size of the leak. After the test has been concluded, the vent control valve will unseal the system after the vacuum has been bled out through the orifice/check valve that has been holding the seal during the test.

column12: SECURE MESSAGE TRANSMISSION USING DYNAMIC SEGMENTATION AND ENCRYPTION
column13: Apparatus, methods, and non-transitory computer readable media for securely sending a digital message from a sending device ( 1 ) to a recipient device ( 3 ) over an open network ( 4 ) such as the Internet. In a method embodiment of the present invention, a system controller ( 5 ) instructs the sending device ( 1 ) to segment the message into a finite number of segments having variable lengths; and assigns a variable number of relay ( 2 ) hops to each segment. The segments then flow from the sending device ( 1 ) to the recipient device ( 3 ) via several layers of conventional network relays ( 2 ). At least some of the segments are encrypted, by the sending device ( 1 ) and/or by one or more autonomous agent modules ( 30 ) operating on the relays ( 2 ). This invention makes it virtually impossible to track what is happening at the relays ( 2 ), or to identify the intended recipient ( 3 ). This virtually eliminates network traffic analysis as a viable means of compromising the security of the communications.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR TRACKING THE SECURITY ENFORCEMENT IN A GRID SYSTEM
column13: The "Grid Security Monitor" tracks the security status of resources in a grid computer system. When a client submits a job to the grid scheduler, the Grid Security Monitor creates a security contract. The security contract comprises all the security credentials needed to access the resource executing the job, as well as privacy and security requirements. The Grid Security Monitor compares the security status of the resource to the requirements of the security contract. If the security status of the resource changes or violates the security contract, then the Grid Security Monitor notifies the client. The Grid Security Monitor has a user interface that allows the client to perform a manual security validation by asking the grid management system to verify the security status of the resource.

column12: Apparatus for generator stator mounting
column13: A generator stator mounting system includes a generator frame comprising an outer annular support coupled to an outer axial bar such as spring bar 78 and an inner axial bar such as key bar 82 that is coupled to the stator. A spring ring 84 is removably coupled to and is circumferentially aligns the inner and outer bars by guide 88 and guide 86. The spring ring guide 86 can comprise a U-bolt clamp 90 about the spring bar and a clamp plate 92 having a radial shim (fig 6, 108). The key bar guide can comprise a machined recess 97 in the inner surface of the spring ring to circumferentially align the stator and have a radial shim (fig 6, 97) and a clamp plate 94 secured by fasteners 98 either side of the spring ring. The key bar can engage a dovetail slot in the stator and the spring bar can extend through axial openings in a ring-shaped plate (fig 2, 76) of the outer annular support. The stator mounting can include plural axially spaced annular supports, plural axially spaced spring rings, and plural circumferentially spaced key bars and spring bars. The mounting system facilitates accurate positioning of the key bars without post-assembly welding or machining.

column12: Method and system to enable touch-free incoming call handling and touch-free outgoing call origination
column13: A system for enabling a user of a communication device to both handle an incoming call and originate an outgoing call without having to touch the communication device, by way of exchange of voice messages with the communication device. The system is operative for receiving a signal produced by a microphone associated with the communication device and for processing this signal in an attempt to detect at least one of a plurality of spoken commands potentially contained therein. The plurality of spoken commands comprises at least one spoken call handling command and at least one spoken call origination command. In response to detecting a spoken call handling command, the system causes handling of an incoming call destined for the communication device in accordance with the detected spoken call handling command. In response to detecting a spoken call origination command, the system causes an attempt to establish an outgoing call using the communication device in accordance with the detected spoken call origination command.

column12: Logical data object reuse in a virtual server
column13: A virtual tape system supporting at least one Write Once Read Many (WORM) logical tape and at least one read-write logical tape, comprises a processor configured to perform a first task and/or a second task. The first task initializes a new logical data object from a single pool of at least two logical data objects, with the new logical data object bound with a member of a media type group consisting of a WORM data object or a read-write data object. The second task reuses one of the logical data objects without manual ejection and reinsertion. The reuse may include the processor configured to cycle the logical data object through a scratch pool as a selected scratch logical data object and mount the selected scratch logical data object with a write from beginning of tape command to bind at least one data attribute to the WORM data object.

column12: Wiederverwendung Logischer Datenobjekte in einem Virtuellen Server
column13: Ein virtuelles Bandsystem, das mindestens ein logisches, einmal beschreibbares und dann nur noch lesbares (WORM-)Band und mindestens ein logisches Schreib-/Lese-Band unterstützt, umfasst einen Prozessor, der so konfiguriert ist, dass er eine erste Aufgabe und/oder eine zweite Aufgabe ausführt. Die erste Aufgabe initialisiert ein neues logisches Datenobjekt aus einem einzigen Pool von mindestens zwei logischen Datenobjekten, wobei das mit einem Mitglied einer Medientypengruppe gebundene neue logische Datenobjekt aus einem WORM-Datenobjekt oder einem Schreib-/Lese-Datenobjekt besteht. Die zweite Aufgabe verwendet, ohne manuelles Auswerfen und Wiedereinlegen, eines der logischen Datenobjekte wieder. Die Wiederverwendung kann den Prozessor umfassen, der so konfiguriert ist, dass er das logische Datenobjekt einen freien Pool als ein ausgewähltes logisches Arbeitsdatenobjekt zyklisch durchlaufen lässt und das ausgewählte logische Arbeitsdatenobjekt mit einem Befehl zum Schreiben ab dem Bandanfang einbindet, um mindestens ein Datenattribut an das WORM-Datenobjekt zu binden.

column12: METHOD AND SYSTEM TO ENABLE TOUCH-FREE INCOMING CALL HANDLING AND TOUCH-FREE OUTGOING CALL ORIGINATION
column13: A system for enabling a user of a communication device to both handle an incoming call and originate an outgoing call without having to touch the communication device, by way of exchange of voice messages with the communication device. The system is operative for receiving a signal produced by a microphone associated with the communication device and for processing this signal in an attempt to detect at least one of a plurality of spoken commands potentially contained therein. The plurality of spoken commands comprises at least one spoken call handling command and at least one spoken call origination command. In response to detecting a spoken call handling command, the system causes handling of an incoming call destined for the communication device in accordance with the detected spoken call handling command. In response to detecting a spoken call origination command, the system causes an attempt to establish an outgoing call using the communication device in accordance with the detected spoken call origination command.

column12: Azoacylacetarylamide/amine condensation products
column13: Azo compounds of formula <FORM:1096362/C4-C5/1> in which X is an aryl or heterocyclic residue, Y is an alkyl, aryl or substituted aryl radical, Z is an aryl or substituted aryl radical and R is an alkyl, substituted alkyl, cycloalkyl or substituted cycloalkyl radical and n is 1 or 2, are prepared by heating a mixture of an azoacylacetarylamide of formula <FORM:1096362/C4-C5/2> the symbols being as above with an amine RNH2 (R is as above), the mixture being heated alone or in solution in a solvent or in aqueous suspension preferably at 70-200 DEG C. column12: Method of pinched line detection for an evaporative emission control system
column13: A method of pinched line detection for an evaporative emission control system to determine if a pinched line is present within the system includes the steps of pulsing a leak detection pump at a predetermined rate and determining if a last pump period is less than a predetermined possible pinched line period limit. The method also includes the steps of concluding a possible pinched line if the last pump period is not less than the possible pinched line period limit and concluding that there is not a possible pinched line if the last pump period is greater than or equal to the possible pinched line period limit.
